<DIV1 TYPE="tract">
	<HEAD TYPE="editorial">I.  DAN JON GAYTRYGE'S SERMON.</HEAD>

<MILESTONE ED="Thornton MS., Lincoln Cathedral Library" N="213 back" UNIT="leaf">
<OPENER>Here begynnes a Sermo&ntail; &thorn;at Da&ntail; Io&hbar;n Gaytryge
made, &thorn;e whilke teeches how scrifte es to be made, & whare-of,
and in scrifte how many thynge&yogh; solde be consederide.  Et est
Petrus sentenciarum discrecione prim&abreve;.</OPENER>

 
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="section"><HEAD TYPE="supplied">The Fourteen Articles of the Creed</HEAD>
<P>Als a grett Doctour schewes in his buke, of a&llbar; <CORR
SIC="ye" RESP="Perry">&thorn;e</CORR>
<NOTE ID="n1">When y stands for &thorn;, &thorn; is printed. F.</NOTE>creatoures &thorn;at Gode made in heue&ntail; and in erthe, in water
and in ayere, or in oghte elles, &thorn;e Souerayne cause & &thorn;e
sky&llbar; whi He mad &thorn;a&mtail; was His awe&ntail; gud wi&llbar;
and His gudnes, Thurg&hbar; &thorn;e whilke gudnes, alls He es
a&llbar; gude, He walde &thorn;at some creatures of &thorn;ase
&thorn;at He made ware communers of &thorn;at blyse &thorn;at
euer-mare lastis.  And for &thorn;at na creatoure myghte come to
&thorn;at blyse<MILESTONE N="214" UNIT="leaf"> with- owtte&ntail; knaweyng of God&dtail;, als
&thorn;at clerkes teches, He made ski&llbar;wyse creatours Angelle and
man, of witt and wysdo&mtail; to knawe God Almyghty&ntail;, and,
thorowe &thorn;aire knawynge, lufe Hym and serue Hy&mtail;, and so
come to &thorn;at blyse &thorn;at &thorn;ay ware made to.  This manere
of knawynge had oure forme-fadyrs in &thorn;e state of Innocence
&thorn;at &thorn;ay ware mad I&nmacr;; and so sulde we hafe hade, if
&thorn;ay had noghte synnede.  Noghte so meki&llbar; als hally saules
hase now in heue&ntail;, Bot meki&llbar; mare &thorn;an ma&ntail; hase
now in erthe.  For oure fourme-fadyrs synned, sayse &thorn;e prophete,
and we bere &thorn;e wykkydnes of &thorn;aire mysdedis; For &thorn;e
knawyng &thorn;at &thorn;ay had of God&dtail; A&llbar;-myghte&ntail;,
they had it of Goddes gyfte at &thorn;aire begynnynge,
with-owtte&ntail; trauayle, or tray, or passinge of ty&mtail;.  And
a&llbar; &thorn;e knaweyng &thorn;at we hafe in &thorn;is werlde of
Hym, es of heryng, and of lerynge, and of techyng of o&thorn;er, of
&thorn;e law and &thorn;e lare &thorn;at langes ti&llbar; Haly
 
<!-- 0002.p2-3.txt -->
<PB N="2">


Kyrke, &thorn;e whilke a&llbar; creatours &thorn;at lufes God
Almyghte&ntail; awe to knawe and to cu&ntail;, and lede &thorn;aire
lyfe afti&rtail;, and swa come to &thorn;at blysse &thorn;at neuer
mare blynnes.</P>

<P>And for-thi &thorn;at meki&llbar; folke now in &thorn;is werlde ne
ere noghte wele ynoghe lerede to knawe God Almyghty, ne lufe Hy&mtail;
ne serue Hy&mtail; als &thorn;ay sulde do, and als &thorn;aire dedys
oftesythes opynly schewes, in gret pere&llbar; to &thorn;a&mtail;, to
lyfe and to saule ; and perawnter &thorn;e defaute may be in
thay&mtail; &thorn;at hase &thorn;ai&rtail; saules for to kepe, and
thay&mtail; sulde teche, &mdash; als prelates and persons, vicars and
prestes, &thorn;at ere halde&ntail; by dett for to lere
&thorn;a&mtail; &mdash; For-thi ou&rtail; Fadi&rtail; &thorn;e byschope
&thorn;at God Almyghty saue, &thorn;at, als Say&ntail; Paule sayse in
his pysti&llbar;, wi&llbar; &thorn;at a&llbar; me&ntail; be safe, and
knawe God Almyghte&ntail;, and namely &thorn;ase vndirlowttes
&thorn;at ti&llbar; hym langes, hase tretide and Ordeyned for &thorn;e
como&ntail; profett, thorowe &thorn;e counce&llbar; of his clergy,
&thorn;at ilkane &thorn;at vndi&rtail; hym hase cure of saule,
Opy&ntail;ly, one ynglysche, apo&ntail; sonnondayes, preche and teche
&thorn;ay&mtail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay hase cure off, &thorn;e lawe and
&thorn;e lare to knawe God Almyghty, &thorn;at principally may be
schewede in theis sexe thynges &mdash; [1] In &thorn;e fourtene poyntes
&thorn;at falles to &thorn;e trowthe, [2] In &thorn;e ten
commandementes &thorn;at Gode hase gyfe&ntail; vs, [3] In &thorn;e
Seue&ntail; Sacramentes &thorn;at er in Haly Kyrke, [4] In &thorn;e
Seue&ntail; werkes of mercy vnti&llbar; oure eue&ntail; crysty&ntail;,
[5] In &thorn;e seue&ntail; vertus &thorn;at ilke ma&ntail; sa&llbar;
vse, [6] And in &thorn;e Seue&ntail; dedly Synnes &thorn;at ilke
ma&ntail; sa&llbar; refuse.  And he byddes and commandes in a&llbar;
&thorn;at he may, &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;at hase cure or kepynge
vndi&rtail; hy&mtail; Enioyne &thorn;ai&rtail; parischennes and
&thorn;ai&rtail; sugettes &thorn;at &thorn;ay here and lere &thorn;ise
ilke sex thynges, and oftesythes reherse &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar;
&thorn;at &thorn;ay cu&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;, and sythe&ntail; teche
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;ai&rtail; childi&rtail;, if &thorn;ay any haue,
whate ty,&mtail; so &thorn;ay are of elde to lere &thorn;a&mtail;.
And &thorn;at persouns and vycars and a&llbar; parische prestis,
Enquere delygently of &thorn;ai&rtail; sugettes In &thorn;e
lenty&ntail; ty&mtail;, whe&ntail; &thorn;ay come to scryfte,
whe&thorn;er &thorn;ay knawe and cu&ntail; &thorn;ise sex thynges; and
if it be funde&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay cu&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;
noghte, &thorn;at &thorn;ay Enjoyne &thorn;a&mtail; appo&ntail; his
behalfe, and Of payne of penance, for to cu&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;.
And for-thi &thorn;at nane sa&llbar; excuse thaym thurghe
vnknawlechynge for to cu&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;,

<PB N="3">

ou&rtail; haly Fadir <MILESTONE N="214 bk." UNIT="leaf">&thorn;e beschope, of his gudnes, hase ordaynede
and bedy&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ay be schewede opynly one ynglysche
amanges &thorn;e folke.</P>

<P>Whare-fore, anence &thorn;e fyrste of &thorn;ise sex thynges
&thorn;at es to knawe, &thorn;e articles &thorn;at falles to &thorn;e
trouthe, &mdash; als gret clerkes teches and schewes in thaire bukes,
&mdash; Thare Falles to &thorn;e faythe<NOTE ID="n2">'faythe' crost thru in the MS.</NOTE> fourtene poyntes; Of &thorn;e
whilke seue&ntail; Falles to Goddes Goddhede, and o&thorn;er
seue&ntail; Falles to Cristes manehede.  &para; The firste poynte
&thorn;at we sa&llbar; trowe of &thorn;e Godhede, Es to trow
stedfastely In a trewe God&dtail;, and &thorn;at na no&thorn;er es for
to trowe In.  &para; The to&thorn;er es, &thorn;at &thorn;e heghe
Fadir of heue&ntail; es stedfaste and sothefaste God&dtail;
Almyghty&ntail;.  &para; The thirde es, &thorn;at Ihesu Criste, Goddes
Sone of heue&ntail;, es sothefastly Gode, eue&ntail; ti&llbar; His
Fadi&rtail;.  &para; The ferthe es, &thorn;at &thorn;e Haly Gaste,
&thorn;at samenly commes of bathe &thorn;e Fadir and &thorn;e Sonne,
es sothefaste Godde, eue&ntail; to &thorn;ay&mtail; bathe; and
&thorn;e whethir noghte twa Goddes, &thorn;e Fadi&rtail; and &thorn;e
Sonne, ne thre Goddes, &thorn;e Fadir and &thorn;e Sonne & &thorn;e
Haly Gaste, Bot thre sere persouns, and noghte bot a God&dtail;.
&para; The fyfte arctecle es, &thorn;at &thorn;e Trynyte, &thorn;e
Fadir and &thorn;e Sonne and &thorn;e Haly Gaste, thre persouns and a
Godd, es makere of heue&ntail; and erthe and of a&llbar; thynges.
&para; The Sexte artycle es, &thorn;at Haly Kirke, oure modire, es
hallyly ane thorow-owte &thorn;e werlde, that es, comonynge and
felawrede of a&llbar; criste&ntail; folke &thorn;at comouns
to-gedi&rtail; in &thorn;e sacramentes, and in o&thorn;er haly thynges
&thorn;at falles ti&llbar; Haly Kyrke, with-owtte&ntail; &thorn;e
whilke ne es na saule hele.  &para; The Seuen&dtail; article &thorn;at
vs awe to trowe es, vppe-rysynge of flesche, and life
with-owtte&ntail; Ende.  For when &thorn;e dede hase sundyrde oure
bodyes and oure saules for a certayne tym, als oure kynd askes, vnto
whe&ntail; &thorn;at God sa&llbar; deme &thorn;e qwykke and &thorn;e
dede, Thane oure saules sa&llbar; turne agayne ti&llbar; oure bodyes,
and we &thorn;ase ilke (and nane o&thorn;er &thorn;a&ntail; we are
nowe), sothefastely sa&llbar; ryse vp in body and saule, &thorn;at
neuer mare sa&llbar; sundire, fra &thorn;at ty&mtail; furthe, bot
Same&ntail; (if we wele doo whiles we er here) wende with God&dtail;
to &thorn;at blysse &thorn;at euer-mare lastes.  And if we euy&llbar;
do, ti&llbar; Endles payne.
 
<!-- 0003.p4-5.txt -->
<PB N="4"></P>


<P>&para; Thir are o&thorn;er seue&ntail; poyntes of Cristes Manhede
&thorn;at are nedfu&llbar; to trowe, ti&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at are
crysty&ntail;.  &para; The fyrste es, &thorn;at Ihesu Criste, Goddes
Sone of heue&ntail;, was sothefastely conceyuede of &thorn;e
made&ntail; Marie, and tuke flesche and blude, and become ma&ntail;
thurghe &thorn;e myghte and &thorn;e strenghe of &thorn;e Haly Gaste,
withowtte&ntail; any merryng of hir modirhede, with-owtte&ntail; any
mynynge of hir mayde&ntail;hede.  &para; The to&thorn;er artecle es,
&thorn;at we sa&llbar; trowe &thorn;at He, God&dtail; and man bathe in
a persoune, was sothefastely of &thorn;at blessyde mayde&ntail;,
God&dtail; gety&ntail; of His Fadire be-fore any tyme, and ma&ntail;,
born of His modir, and broghte furthe in tyme.  &para; The thirde
poynte &thorn;at we sa&llbar; trowe es, Cristes Passione that He
tholede bodyly for synfu&llbar; ma&ntail;-kynde, How He was betraysede
with His disciple, and take&ntail; with &thorn;e Iewes, bete&ntail;
with scourges, &thorn;at na skyn&ntail; helde, naylede one &thorn;e
rude, and corounde with thornes, and many o&thorn;er harde paynes, and
dyede at &thorn;e laste.  &para; The ferthe artecle es, &thorn;at
whene He was dede, and His body tane dou&ntail;, and wonde&ntail; and
dolue&ntail;, &yogh;it &thorn;e whi&llbar;s His body lay in &thorn;e
graue, &thorn;e gaste with &thorn;e Godhede wente vnto Helle, and
heryede it, and tuke owte &thorn;ase &thorn;at ware &thorn;are-in, als
Adam and Eue and o&thorn;er <MILESTONE N="215" UNIT="leaf">Forme-fadyrs whilke He in His forluke
walde &thorn;at ware sauede.  &para; The fyfte poynte es, &thorn;at
one &thorn;e thirde day after &thorn;at He dyede, He rase fra dede to
lyfe, Sothefaste God&dtail; and ma&ntail; in body and in saule.  For
als He dyede in seknes of oure manhede, So He rase thurghe strenghe of
His Godhede, and swa dystroyed oure dede thurg&hbar; His diynge, and
quykkynd vs unto lyfe thurghe His rysesynge.  &para; The sexte artecle
es, &thorn;at we sa&llbar; trowe &thorn;at one &thorn;e fourtede day
eftyr &thorn;at He rase, Thurg&hbar; strenghe of Hym-selfe, He steye
in-ti&llbar; Heue&ntail;, whare oure kynde es nowe in His blyssyde
personne, noghte anely euynne ne mete ti&llbar; His ange&llbar;s, Bot
hey coround kynge abowne a&llbar; His ange&llbar;s, &thorn;at be-fore
ty&mtail; was lesse &thorn;an &thorn;e kynde of ange&llbar;s.  &para;
The seuend article es, &thorn;at righte als He dyede, and eftirwarde
rase, and stey in-ti&llbar; heue&ntail;, Righte swa sa&llbar; He come
apo&ntail; &thorn;e laste day, Bathe for to deme &thorn;e qwykke and
&thorn;e dede, whare a&llbar; &thorn;e folke &thorn;at euer was, or
es, or sa&llbar; be, sa&llbar; sothefastely be schewede and

sene be-fore Hy&mtail;, and ilke a ma&ntail; answere of his awe&ntail;
dedis, and be saued or dampnede whe&thorn;er so he serues; For, als
His ryghtwysenes now es mengede with mercy, swa sa&llbar; it thane be
with-owtte&ntail; mercy.</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Secundo.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Decem precepta Dei.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The ten Commandementis.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E secund thyng of &thorn;e Sex to knawe God Almyghte&ntail;
es, &thorn;e te&ntail; Commandmentes &thorn;at He hase gyffe&ntail;
vs. Of &thorn;e whilke te&ntail;, &thorn;e thre &thorn;at ere firste,
awe us hallyly to halde anence oure God&dtail;; and &thorn;e
Seue&ntail; &thorn;at ere eftyre, anence oure eue&ntail;
criste&ntail;.  &para; The firste comandement charges vs, and teches
vs, &thorn;at we leue ne lowte na false goddes. And in &thorn;is
commandement es forbode&ntail; vs alky&ntail; mysbyleues and a&llbar;
mawmetryes, a&llbar; false enchauntementes, and a&llbar; soceryes,
a&llbar; false charmes, and a&llbar; wichecraftes, &thorn;at me&ntail;
of myssehyleue traystes appo&ntail;, or hopes any helpe I&ntail;,
with-owtte&ntail; God Almyghte&ntail;.  &para; The to&thorn;er
commandement byddes vs noghte take in ydillchipe, ne in vayne,
&thorn;e name of oure Lorde God&dtail;, so &thorn;at we trowe noghte
in His name bot &thorn;at es sothefaste, &thorn;at we swere noghte by
His name bot it be byhouely, and &thorn;at we neue&ntail; noghte His
name bot wirchipfully.  &para; The thirde commandement es, &thorn;at
we halde and halowe oure haly day, &thorn;e Sonondaye, and a&llbar;
o&thorn;er &thorn;at falles to &thorn;e &yogh;ere, &thorn;at er
ordeynede to halowe thurg&hbar; Haly Kyrke.  In &thorn;e whilke dayes
a&llbar; folke, bathe lerede and lawede, awe to gyffe &thorn;a&mtail;
gudly to Goddes seruyce, to here and say it efter &thorn;aire state
es, in wirchipe of Godd All-myghty and of His gud halowes, noghte
&thorn;a&ntail; for to tente to tary with &thorn;e werlde, ne lyffe in
lykynge ne luste, &thorn;at &thorn;e flesche &yogh;ernes, Bot gudly to
serue God&dtail; in clennes of lyfe.  &para; The fert&hbar;e
commandement byddes vs doo wyrchipe to Fadire and to modire, noghte<MILESTONE
N="215 bk." UNIT="leaf">
anely to fleschely fadyr and modire, &thorn;at getes vs and fosters vs
furthe in &thorn;e werlde, bot ti&llbar; oure gastely Fadire &thorn;at
hase heuede of vs, and teches vs to lyffe ti&llbar; hele of
 
<!-- 0004.p6-7.txt -->
<PB N="6">

oure saules, and ti&llbar; oure gastely modyr, &thorn;at es, Haly
Kyrke, to be bouxome &thorn;are-to, and saue &thorn;e ryghte of it,
For it es modir ti&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at cristenly lyffes, and
alswa ti&llbar; ilke ma&ntail; &thorn;at wyrchipfu&llbar; es, for to
do wyrchipe eftere &thorn;at it es. &para; The fyfte comandement
byddes vs &thorn;at we sla na ma&ntail;, &thorn;at es to say, bodyly
ne gastely no&thorn;er; For als many we sla, in &thorn;at at we may,
als we sclaundire or bakbyte or falsely dcffames, or fandes for to
confounde &thorn;aym &thorn;at noghte serues, or withdrawes lyfelade
fra &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at hase nede, if we be of hauynge for to
helpe &thorn;a&mtail;.  &para; The sexte commandment forbeddes us to
sy&ntail; or for to foly fleschely with any woma&ntail;, ow&thorn;er
sybbe or fremmede, wedde or vnwedde, or any fleschely knawynge or dede
haue with any, o&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;e Sacrament of matremoyne
excuse&yogh;, and &thorn;e lawe and &thorn;e lare of Haly Kyrke
teches.  &para; The seuen&dtail; byddis vs &thorn;at we sa&llbar;
noghte stele: In whilke es forbode&ntail; vs robbyng and reuyng, and
a&llbar; wrangwyse takynge or with-haldynge, or hydynge or helelynge
of o&thorn;er menes gudes, agaynes &thorn;aire witt and &thorn;aire
wi&llbar; &thorn;at hase ryghte to &thorn;ay&mtail;.  &para; The
aughte&ntail; commandement byddes vs &thorn;at we sa&llbar; bere no
false wytnes agaynes oure eue&ntail; criste&ntail;: In &thorn;e whilke
es forbode&ntail; vs a&llbar; manere of lesynges, False consperacye
and false swerynge, whare-thurghe oure eue&ntail; cristy&ntail; may
lese &thorn;ayre cate&llbar;, Fait&hbar;, Fauour or Fame, or anything
e&llbar;s, whe&thorn;er it be in gastely or in bodyly gudes.  &para;
The nyende commandement es, &thorn;at we &yogh;erne noghte oure
neghtboure house: In whilke es forbode&ntail; a&llbar; wrangwyse
couetyse of land or of lythe, or of oghte elles &thorn;at may noghte
be lyftede ne raysede fra &thorn;e grounde, als thynge &thorn;at es
stedfaste, and may noghte be styrrede.  &para; The ten&dtail;
commandement an &thorn;e laste es, &thorn;at we &yogh;erne noghte
&thorn;e wyefe of oure neghteboure ne of oure euy&ntail;
criste&ntail;, ne his mayde&ntail;, ne his knaue, ne his oxe, ne his
asse : In &thorn;e whilke es forbode&ntail; vs to &yogh;erne or to
take any thynge &thorn;at may be styrride of o&thorn;er
m&emacr;&nmacr;s gudes, als robes or reches or o&thorn;er cate&llbar;,
&thorn;at we hafe na gude titi&llbar; ne na ryghte to; For what thyng
so we take or getes one o&thorn;er wyse &thorn;an &thorn;e lawe and
&thorn;e lare of Haly Kyrke teches, we may noghte be assoylede of
&thorn;e trespase bot if we

<PB N="7">

make assethe, in &thorn;at &thorn;at we may, to &thorn;a&mtail;
&thorn;at we harmede with haldande &thorn;aire gude.  And in case
&thorn;at we hafe thurghe false athes, als in assises or o&thorn;er
enquestes, wetandly or willfully gerte oure eue&ntail; cristy&ntail;
lesse &thorn;aire patremoyne or &thorn;aire heritage, or falsely be
dyssessede of lande or of lythe, or false deuorce be made, or any
ma&ntail; da&mmacr;pnede, &thorn;ofe a&llbar; we do &thorn;at we may
to &thorn;e party, &yogh;it may we noghte be assoylede of &thorn;e
trespas, bot of oure beschoppe, or of hym &thorn;at hase his powere,
For swylke caas es ryuely reseruede ti&llbar; hy&mtail; selue&ntail;.
&para; Thise te&ntail; commandemente&yogh; &thorn;at I hafe now
rekkenede er vmbylowkede in twa of &thorn;e gospe&llbar;e.  The tane
es, &thorn;at we luffe God&dtail; ouer a&llbar; thynges; The
to&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="216" UNIT="leaf"> es, &thorn;at we lufe oure eue&ntail; criste&ntail;
hallely in oure herte als we do oure selue&ntail;; For Godd awe vs to
lufe hally with herte, with a&llbar; oure myghte, with a&llbar; oure
thoghte, with worde and with dede. Oure euy&ntail; cryste&ntail;,
als-swa awe vs to lufe vn-to &thorn;at ilke gude &thorn;at we lufe
oure-selfe, &thorn;at es, &thorn;at &thorn;ay wele fare in body and in
saule, and come to &thorn;at ilke blysse &thorn;at we thynke to ; and
whate-so-euer &thorn;at he bee, &thorn;at &thorn;ise twa wele
&yogh;emes, a&llbar; &thorn;e te&ntail; commandementes forsothe he
fulfilles.</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="section">

<HEAD>Tertio.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">Septem sunt Sacramenta Ecclesie.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The Seuene Sacramentes of Haly Kyrke.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E thirde thynge of &thorn;e Sex &thorn;at I firste touchide,
es &thorn;e Seue&ntail; Sacramentes &thorn;at Haly Kirke gyffes,
thurg&hbar;e prelates and o&thorn;er prestes &thorn;at hase &thorn;e
powere.  Of whilke seue&ntail;, the first fyve ilke criste&ntail;
ma&ntail; awe lawefully to take efter his elde es; and twa lyes in
&thorn;aire will &thorn;at ressayues &thorn;ay&mtail;.  &para; The
firste sacrament of seue&ntail; es oure `bapty&mtail;,' &thorn;at we
take &thorn;e firste ty&mtail; &thorn;at we be-co&mtail;
cristy&ntail;.  In whilke, bathe &thorn;e firste syn&ntail; &thorn;at
we ere borne wit&hbar;, and alky&ntail; o&thorn;er synnes, ere
wasche&ntail; awaye, &thorn;at we ere fylede wit&hbar; are we take it;
and &thorn;e trouthe of Haly Kyrke es take&ntail; &thorn;are-i&ntail;,
with- owtte&ntail; whilke na synfu&llbar; mans saule may be sauede.
And ti&llbar; &thorn;is sacrament Falles foure thynges, if it
sa&llbar; ryghtely be tane als Haly Kirke teches.  Ane es, ryghte
sayeyng and carpyng
 
<!-- 0005.p8-9.txt -->
<PB N="8">

of &thorn;e wordes &thorn;at hym awe for to say &thorn;at gyffes
&thorn;is sacrament, &thorn;at ere &thorn;ise : &mdash; ` I Baptise &thorn;e
in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e Fadir and &thorn;e Sonne and &thorn;e
Haly Gaste.'  Ane o&thorn;er es, &thorn;at it be done anely in watire,
For na no&thorn;er licoure es lefulle &thorn;are-fore.  &THORN;e
thirde es, &thorn;at he &thorn;at gyffes &thorn;is sacrement be in
witt and in wi&llbar; for to gyffe it.  And &thorn;e ferthe es,
&thorn;at he &thorn;at takes it be, no&thorn;er of lerede nor of
lewde, Baptisede be-fore; For if &thorn;e preste be in were of hym
&thorn;at sa&llbar; take it, whethire he be baptisede or he be noghte,
&thorn;an sa&llbar; he say &thorn;e wordes one &thorn;is wyese, `If
&thorn;ou be noghte baptisede, I baptise &thorn;e in &thorn;e name of
&thorn;e Fadire and &thorn;e Sone and &thorn;e Haly Gaste.'  &para;
The secunde sacrament es `confermynge,' &thorn;at &thorn;e byschope
gyffes to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at ere baptisede, &thorn;at gyffes
thorowe his powere to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at takes it &thorn;e
grace and &thorn;e gyfte of &thorn;e Haly Gaste, to make
&thorn;ay&mtail; mare stalleworthe &thorn;an &thorn;ay ware be-fore,
to stande agaynes &thorn;e fende and dedly sy&ntail;; &thorn;at nane
hase powere to do bot &thorn;e byschope allane, &thorn;at hase the
state and &thorn;e stede of Cristes Appostilles.  &para; The thirde
sacrament es callede `penance,' &thorn;at es, sothefaste forthynkynge
&thorn;at we hafe of oure sy&ntail;, with-owtte&ntail; wi&llbar; or
thoghte to turne agayne to it.  And &thorn;is sacrament must haue thre
thynges: &mdash; Ane es, sorowe in oure herte &thorn;at we hafe synnede.
Ano&thorn;er es, opy&ntail; scrifte of mouthe, how we hafe synnede.
The [third es, satisfaccion, &thorn;at we maun do for oure sy&ntail;].<NOTE ID="n3">A sentence is here wanting through error of the scribe.  [For 'satisfaccion' see Wm. of Shoreham's Poems 39/1078, 'Sorwe, schryfte, and edbote.' F.]</NOTE>  <MILESTONE
N="216 bk." UNIT="leaf">&para; &THORN;ise thre, with gud wi&llbar; to forsake oure
sy&ntail;, clense&yogh; vs and wasches vs of alky&ntail; sy&ntail;.
&para; The ferthe es, `&thorn;e Sacrament of &thorn;e Autyr,' Cristes
awe&ntail; body in lyknes of brede, als hale als He tuke it of
&thorn;e blysside mayde&ntail;, the whilke, ilke ma&ntail; and
woma&ntail; &thorn;at of elde es, awe for to rescheyue anes in
&thorn;e &yogh;ere, &thorn;at es at say, at &thorn;e pasc&hbar;, als
Haly Kyrke vses, when &thorn;ay ere clensede of sy&ntail; thurg&hbar;e
penance, O payne of doynge owte of Haly Kyrke, bot if &thorn;ay
forbere it by ski&llbar;wyse cause, &thorn;at awe to be knawe&ntail;
to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at sa&llbar; gyffe it; For he &thorn;at tase
it worthily, tase his saluacyone; and wha-so takes it vnworthily,
<PB N="9">
tase his dampnacione. &para; The fyfte sacrament es `&thorn;e laste
Enoyntynge with oyle,' &thorn;at es halowede and handelyde of prestes;
&thorn;e whilke sacrament awe anely to be gyffe&ntail; to
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at he wate ere of skillwyse elde, and &thorn;at
he sese sekyrly in pere&llbar;e of dede, in lyghtenes and alegeance of
&thorn;aire sekenes, if Godde wi&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ay turne
agayne to &thorn;e hele, and als in forgyffnes of venial synnes, and
in lessynge of payne if &thorn;ay passe he&thorn;e&ntail;.  &para; The
Sexte sacrament of Haly Kyrke es `ordire,' &thorn;at gyffes powere to
&thorn;am &thorn;at ryghtwysly tase it, For to serue in Haly Kirke
efter &thorn;aire state es, and to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at takes
&thorn;e ordyre of preste, for to synge messe, and for to mynystre
&thorn;e Sacramentes of Haly Kyrke, &thorn;at to &thorn;a&mtail;
fallys, Eftyr &thorn;e state &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe, and &thorn;aire
degre askes.  &para; The seuen&dtail; Sacrament es ` Matrymoyne,'
&thorn;at es, lawefu&llbar; festynnynge be-twyx ma&ntail; and
woma&ntail; at &thorn;aire bathere assente, for to lyffe same&ntail;
with-owtte&ntail; any lowssynge, whi&llbar;s &thorn;aire lyfe lastes,
in remedy of sy&ntail; and getynge of grace, if it be tane in gude
Entente and clennes of lyfe.</P></DIV2>

<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The Ferthe thyng of &thorn;e Sex.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">These be &thorn;e Seuene werkes of Mercy Bodyly.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;e ferthe thynge of &thorn;e Sex to knawe God&dtail;
Almyghty, &thorn;at vs byhoues fullfi&llbar; in a&llbar; &thorn;at we
maye, ere &thorn;e seue&ntail; dedis of mercy vnti&llbar; oure
eue&ntail; criste&ntail;, &thorn;at God&dtail; sa&llbar; reherse vs
apo&ntail; &thorn;e dredfu&llbar; day of dome, and wiet howe we haue
done &thorn;a&mtail; here in &thorn;is lyfe, als sayne Mathewe makes
mynde in his gospe&llbar;e.  &para; Of whilke, &thorn;e firste es, to
fede &thorn;ay&mtail; &thorn;at er hunngry.  &para; The to&thorn;er
es, to gyffe &thorn;aym drynke &thorn;at er thristy.  &para; The
thyrde es, for to clethe &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at er clatheles or
nakede.  &para; The ferthe es, for to herber &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at
er houseles.  &para; The fyfte es, for to vesete &thorn;a&mtail;
&thorn;at lyes in sekenes.  &para; The Sexte es, for to helpe
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at lyes or er in presou&ntail;.  &para; The
Seuen&dtail; es, to bery dede me&ntail; &thorn;at hase myster.  &para;
&THORN;ise ere the Seue&ntail; bodyly dedis of mercy &thorn;at ilke
ma&ntail; awe to doo &thorn;at es myghtty.  &para; &THORN;ar are of
mercy alswa Seue&ntail; gastely dedis &thorn;at vs awe to doo
ti&llbar; &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at hase nede ti&llbar; vs.  &para;
Ane es, to consaile and wysse &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at are wy&llbar;.
&para; Ano&thorn;er es, to
 
<!-- 0006.p10-11.txt -->
<PB N="10">

chasty &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at wyrkkys i&llbar;.  &para; &THORN;e
thyrd <MILESTONE N="217" UNIT="leaf">es, to solauce thaym &thorn;at er sorowefu&llbar;, and comforthe
thay&mtail;.  &para; The ferthe es, to pray for thay&mtail; &thorn;at
ere synfu&llbar;.  &para; &THORN;e fyfte es, to be thole-mode
whe&ntail; me&ntail; mysdose vs.  &para; &THORN;e Sexte es, Gladly to
forgyffe when me&ntail; haues greuede vs.  &para; The seuen&dtail;,
when me&ntail; askes vs for to lere thaym, if we cu&ntail; mare
&thorn;an &thorn;ay, for to lere thaym.  &para;, &THORN;ise
vn-ti&llbar; oure neghtebours ere fu&llbar; nedfu&llbar;, and to
&thorn;am &thorn;at duse thay&mtail; wondi&rtail; medefu&llbar;;
Fo&rtail; he sa&llbar; Mercy &thorn;at Mercyfu&llbar; es ; and
ma&ntail; with-owtte&ntail; Mercy, of Mercy sall mysse.</P>

<P>vij. opera misericordie corporalia:,: vnde versus : &mdash;  Vestio, cibo,
poto, redimo, tego, colligo, condo.</P>

<P>vij. opera misericordie spiritualia : &mdash;  Consule, castiga, solare,
remitte, fer, ora, Instrue, si poteris, sic Christo carus
haberis.</P></DIV2>


<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="section">
<HEAD>The Fifte thyng of &thorn;e Sex.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The seuene gastely vertus.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E fyfte thynge of &thorn;e Sex to knawe God Almyghte&ntail;,
are &thorn;e Seue&ntail; vertus &thorn;at Haly Writte teches.  Of
whilke seue&ntail;, &thorn;e thre first &thorn;at are hede thewes,
teches vs how to hafe vs vn-to God Almyghtty; and &thorn;e foure
teches vs swa for to lyffe &thorn;at it be bathe lykande to God&dtail;
and to ma&ntail;.  &para; &THORN;e firste vertu es `trouthe,'
wharethurghe we trow anely in God&dtail; &thorn;at made a&llbar;
thynges, with a&llbar; &thorn;e o&thorn;er vertus I touchede be-fore.
And &thorn;is es nedfu&llbar; ti&llbar; a&llbar; &thorn;at cristenly
lyffes ; For trouthe es begynnynge of a&llbar; gude dedis; For
no&thorn;er es trouthe worthe with-owtte&ntail; gud werk, ne na werke
with-owtte&ntail; trouthe may pay God&dtail; Almyghtty.  &para;
&THORN;e to&thorn;er gude thewe or vertue es ` hope,' &thorn;at es, a
sekyr habydynge of gastely gude, thurghe Goddes gudnes and oure gude
dedis, for to co&mtail; to &thorn;at blysse &thorn;at neuer mare
blynnes, Noghte anely in trayste of Goddes gudnes, ne allanly in
trayste of oure gude dedis, Bot in trayste of thay&mtail; bathe
whe&ntail; &thorn;ay are bathe Samme&ntail;; For no&thorn;er sa&llbar;
we fa&llbar; sa ferre in-ti&llbar; whanhope &thorn;at we ne sa&llbar;
traiste to hafe

<PB N="11">

&thorn;at blysse if we wele do; Ne we sa&llbar; noghte co&mtail; so
ferre in-to ouerhope for to trayste so meki&llbar; in Goddes gudnes
&thorn;at we sa&llbar; hope to haue &thorn;at blysse with-owtte&ntail;
gude dedys.  &para; &THORN;e thirde vertue or thewe es `charyte,'
&thorn;e whylke es a dere lufe &thorn;at vs awe vn-ti&llbar;
God&dtail; Almyghtty als for Hym selfe, and ti&llbar; oure
euencriste&ntail; for God Almyghtty&ntail;; For &thorn;e tane may
noghte be lufede with-owtte&ntail; &thorn;e to&thorn;er, als Sayn
Io&hbar;n &thorn;e gospellere sayse in his pysti&llbar;.  ` &THORN;at
commandement,' he saise, ` hafe we of God&dtail;<MILESTONE
N="217 bk." UNIT="leaf">  &thorn;at
wha-sa-euer lufes Gode, lufes his euencristy&ntail;.  For he &thorn;at
lufes noghte his bro&thorn;er wha&mtail; he may see, how sulde he lufe
God wha&mtail; he sese noghte ?` &para; &THORN;e ferthe vertue or
thewe es `ryghtwysenes,' &thorn;at es, to &yogh;elde to a&llbar;
me&ntail; &thorn;at we awe &thorn;a&mtail;, For to do to ilke a
ma&ntail; &thorn;at vs awe to doo, for to wirchipe tha&mtail;
&thorn;at ere worthy, For to helpe &thorn;e pure &thorn;at er nedy, to
do no gyle ne wrange vn-to na ma&ntail;, Bot for to do &thorn;at
ski&llbar; es vnti&llbar; ilke mane.  &para; &THORN;e fyfte vertue or
thewe es `sleghte or sleghenes,' &thorn;at wysses vs to be-warre with
wathes of &thorn;e werlde; For it kennes vs to knawe &thorn;e gud and
&thorn;e i&llbar;, and alswa to sundire &thorn;e tane fra &thorn;e
to&thorn;er, and for to leue &thorn;at es euy&llbar;, and take to
&thorn;e gude, and of twa gud thynges for to chese &thorn;e better.
&para; &THORN;e Sexte vertue es `strenghe or stalworthnes,' noghte
anely of body, bot of herte and wi&llbar;, euynly to suffire &thorn;e
wele and &thorn;e waa, welthe or wandret&hbar;, whethire so betyde,
and &thorn;at oure herte be noghte to hye for na wele-fare, ne
ouermekill vndire for nane euy&llbar; fare, Bot styffely for to stande
agaynes oure faas, whethir &thorn;ay be bodyly or &thorn;ay be
gastely, swa &thorn;at na fulle fandynge make vs to falle ne be false
in oure fayt&hbar;e agaynes God Almyghtty. &para; &THORN;e Seuend
vertue and &thorn;e laste es, `methe or methefulnes,' &thorn;at kepes
vs fra owterage and haldes vs in euenhede, lettes fulle lykynge and
luste of &thorn;e flesche, and &yogh;emes vs fra &yogh;ernynges of
werldly gudes, and kepes in clennes of body and of saule.  For methe
es mesure and mett of a&llbar; &thorn;at we do, if we lyffe skillwysly
als &thorn;e lawe teches.
 
<!-- 0007.p12-13.txt -->
<PB N="12"></P></DIV2>

<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="section"><HEAD>The sexte thyng and &thorn;e laste.</HEAD>

<P>&THORN;E sexte thynge, and &thorn;e laste of &thorn;ase I firste
towchede es, &thorn;e Seue&ntail; heuede or dedly synnes &thorn;at
ilke a ma&ntail; and woma&ntail; awe for to knawe to flee and forhewe,
For folkes may noghte flee &thorn;a&mtail; bot &thorn;ay knawe
thay&mtail;.  &para; Pride &para; and Enuye, &para; Wreth &para; and
Glotonye, &para; Couetyse &para; and Slouthe, &para; and Lecherye.
And for-&thorn;i er &thorn;ay callede Seue&ntail; heuede Synnes, for
&thorn;at all o&thorn;er commes of thay&mtail;; and for-&thorn;i er
&thorn;ay callede dedely synnes, for &thorn;ay gastely slaa ilke manes
& womanes saule &thorn;at es haunkede in a&llbar;e or in any of
thay&mtail;.  Whare-fore &thorn;e wyese ma&ntail; byddes in his buke `
als fra &thorn;e face of &thorn;e neddyre, fande to flee sy&ntail;.'
For als &thorn;e veny&mtail; of &thorn;e neddire slaas manes body, Swa
&thorn;e veny&mtail; of syn slaas manes saule.  &para; The firste of
&thorn;ise Seue&ntail; synnes es callede `Pryde,' &thorn;at es, a
lykande heghenees of a manes herte, Of offyce or of heghe state, or
o&thorn;er noblaye &thorn;at he ou&thorn;er haues of kynde or of
grace, or he hopes &thorn;at he haues mare &thorn;a&ntail;
anothire. And of &thorn;is wikkede syn&ntail; commes some sere spyces:
&mdash; Boste and <MILESTONE N="218" UNIT="leaf">auauntynge and vn-bouxsomnes, despite, and ypocrisy
and vnhamlynes, and o&thorn;er &thorn;at ofte ere sene amanges prowde
me&ntail;.  &para; The secunde dedely syn&ntail; es hatte&ntail;
`Enuy,' &thorn;at es, a sorowe and a syte of &thorn;e wele-fare, and a
ioy of &thorn;e euy&llbar; fare, of oure eue&ntail;cristen: Of whilke
syn&ntail;, many spyces sprenges and spredes.  Ane es, hateredy&ntail;
to speke or here oghte be spoke&ntail;, &thorn;at may sow&ntail; vn-to
gude to &thorn;aym &thorn;at &thorn;ay hate.  Ane-o&thorn;er, false
juggynge or dome of &thorn;aire dedis, and ay turne vn-to euy&llbar;
&thorn;at es done to gude.  &THORN;e thirde es `bakbyttynge,' to saye
be-hynde &thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;at we wi&llbar; noghte avowe ne saye
be-fore &thorn;a&mtail; ; whare noghte anely he &thorn;at spekes
&thorn;e euy&llbar;, bot he &thorn;at heres it be spoke&ntail;, es for
to blame; For, ware &thorn;are na herere, &thorn;are ware na
bakbyttere.  &para; &THORN;e thirde dedly syn&ntail; or heuede
sy&ntail; es `wrethe,' &thorn;at es, a wykkede stirrynge or bollenynge
of herte, whare-fore a man wilnes for to wreke hy&mtail;, or wykkydly
to venge hym, appon his euy&ntail;cristy&ntail;.  And of &thorn;is
wykkede sy&ntail; commes stryvynge and

<PB N="13">

flytynge, with many false athes and many foule wordes, Sclaundere, for
to for-do a man's gude fame, Feghtynge and Felony, and ofte
manes-slaughtere, and many ma &thorn;at nowe es [na] nede for to be
neuenede.  &para; &THORN;e fferthe dedly syn&ntail; me&ntail; calles
`glotonye,' &thorn;at es, ane vnskilwyse lykynge or lufe in taste or
in takynge of mete or of drynke. And &thorn;ise trespas me&ntail; duse
apponne sere wyse : &mdash; Ane es, ou&thorn;er ouer arely or ouer late, or
ouer oftesythe, for to ete or drynke bot if nede gere it. Ane
o&thorn;er es, for to lyffe ouer delycately.  &THORN;e thirde es, for
to ete or drynke ouer meky&llbar;.  &THORN;e fert&hbar;e es, ouer
hastely to ete or to drynke.  &THORN;e fifte es, to compas & caste
appo&ntail; whate wyese we may gette dylicious metis or drynkes to
fulfi&llbar; &thorn;e lykynges and &thorn;e lustes of &thorn;e
flesc&hbar; o&thorn;er &thorn;an we may gudly lede oure lyffe with,
Secundum<NOTE ID="n4">MS. 'Sonde,' the probable miscopying of some contraction. Mr. J. A. Herbert suggests 'Secundum,' as the Latin words (not a verse) which follow mean 'Very hastily, delicately, too eagerly, anxiously,' state 4 of the abovesaid 5 ways to be avoided in eating and drinking.</NOTE> versum,</P>


<P>Prepropere, laute, nimis ardenter, studios&egrave;.</P>

<P>&para; &THORN;e fyfte dedly sy&ntail; es callede `Couetyse,'
&thorn;at es, a wrangwyse wilnynge or &yogh;ernynge to haue any maner
of gude vs awe noghte.  And &thorn;is es donne pryncypally appo&ntail;
twy&ntail; wyese.  Ane es, wrangwysely to get any thynge &thorn;at
oure likynge or oure lufe lyghtes apo&ntail;, als be Sacrelege or by
symony, falsehede or okyr, or o&thorn;er gelery, whilke &thorn;ise
worldely me&ntail; er wounte for to vse &thorn;at castes &thorn;aire
conaundenes swa vn-to couetyse &thorn;at &thorn;ay ne rekke
whe&thorn;er it be with ryghte or with wrange, bot &thorn;at &thorn;ay
may gette &thorn;at at &thorn;aire herte &yogh;ernes.  Ano&thorn;er
es, wrangwisely to halde &thorn;at at es gety&ntail;, &thorn;at es,
whe&ntail; we wi&llbar; noghte do to God&dtail; Almyghte&ntail; ne
ti&llbar; Haly Kyrke, ne ti&llbar; oure eue&ntail;cristy&ntail;,
&thorn;at vs awe for to do by dett and by lawe, bot anely haldes
&thorn;at we hafe for ese of oure selfe&ntail;, whare noghte anely he
&thorn;at wrangwysly getes, bot he &thorn;at wrangwysely haldes,
falles in &thorn;e syn&ntail;.  &para; &THORN;e sexte dedly syn&ntail;
es `slewthe or slawenes,' &thorn;at es, a hertly angere or anoye
ti&llbar; vs of any gastely gud &thorn;at we sa&llbar; do.  <MILESTONE
N="218 bk." UNIT="leaf">And of
&thorn;is wikkede synn comes sere spyces: &mdash; Ane es, latesommes
or lyte to drawe apo&ntail; lenghte or to lache
 
<!-- 0008.p14-15.txt -->
<PB N="14">

any gude dedis &thorn;at we sa&llbar; do &thorn;at may turne vs
ti&llbar; helpe or hele of oure saules. Ano&thorn;er es, a `dullnes or
heuenes of herte' &thorn;at lettes vs for to lufe oure Lorde God
Almyghte&ntail;, or any lykynge to hafe in His seruyse.  &THORN;e
thirde es, `ydillchipe,' &thorn;at ouer meky&llbar; es hauntede,
&thorn;at makes lathe to begyn&ntail; any gude dedis, and lyghtly dose
vs to leue whe&ntail; oghte es begu&ntail;, and &thorn;are whare we
ere kyndely borne for to swynke, als &thorn;e feule es kyndely brede
for to flie, It haldes vs euermare in ese agayne oure kynde, For
Idillnes es Enemy to criste&ntail; ma&ntail; saule, stepmodire and
stamerynge agaynes gude thewes, and witter- wyssynge and waye
ti&llbar; alky&ntail; vices.  &para; &THORN;e Seuen&dtail; dedely
sy&ntail; es hatte&ntail; `lychery' &thorn;at es, a foule lykynge or
luste of &thorn;e flesche.  And of &thorn;is foule sy&ntail; comes
many sere spyces: &mdash; Ane es `Fornycacyone,' a fleschely synn be-twyxe
ane anlypy ma&ntail; and ane anlypy woma&ntail;: and for-thi &thorn;at
it [es] agaynes &thorn;e lawe, & &thorn;e leue and &thorn;e lare
&thorn;at Haly Kirke haldes, it is dedly sy&ntail; to &thorn;aym
&thorn;at it duse.  Ano&thorn;er es `Avowtry, and &thorn;at es
spousebreke, whe&thorn;er it be bodyly or it be gastely, &thorn;at
greuosere and gretter es &thorn;an &thorn;e to&thorn;er. &THORN;e
thirde es `Incest,' &thorn;at es, whe&ntail; a ma&ntail; synnes
fleschely with any of his sybb frendes, or any o&thorn;er &thorn;at es
of his affynyte gastely or bodyly, whe&thorn;er so it be.  O&thorn;er
spyces many sprynges of &thorn;is sy&ntail; &thorn;at ouer mekill es
knawe&ntail; and kende in &thorn;is werlde with &thorn;aym &thorn;at
ledes &thorn;aire lyfe als &thorn;aire flesche &yogh;ernes.</P>

<P>&para; &THORN;ise are &thorn;e sex thynges &thorn;at I hafe spoken
off, &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe of Haly Kirke lyes maste in ; The whilke
we er halde&ntail; to knawe and to cu&ntail;, if we sa&llbar; knawe
God Almyghty, and come ti&llbar; His blysse.  &para; And for to gyffe
&yogh;ow better wy&llbar; for to cu&ntail; thaym, Oure ffadir &thorn;e
beschope grauntes of his grace Fourty dayes of pardou&ntail; ti&llbar;
a&llbar; &thorn;at cunnes thaym, and ratyfyes alswa &thorn;at
o&thorn;er me&ntail; gyffes, Swa meki&llbar; coueites he &thorn;e hele
of &yogh;our saules.  For &yogh;ife &yogh;e conandely knawe &thorn;ise
Sex thynges, thurg&hbar; thaym sa&llbar; &yogh;e cu&ntail; knawe
God&dtail; Almyghty, whaym, als Sayne Io&hbar;n sayse in his gospelle,
cunnandely for to knawe swylke als He es, It es endles lyfe and
lastande blysse.  To &thorn;e whilke blysse He brynge vs,
<PB N="15">
oure Lorde Gode Almyghty! Ame&ntail; ! Ame&ntail;! Ame&ntail;!  Per
Dominum nostrum Iesum Christum, qui cum Deo <CORR SIC="patri" RESP="Perry">patr&ebreve;</CORR> et Spiritu
Sancto viuit et regnat omnipotens deus in secula seculorum.  Amen!
Amen! Amen !
 
<!-- 0009.p16-17.txt -->
<PB N="16"></P></DIV2></DIV1>


<DIV1 TYPE="tract">

<HEAD TYPE="editorial">II. THE MIRROR OF SAINT EDMUND.</HEAD>

<MILESTONE
ED="Robert Thornton's Manuscript, Lincoln Cathedral Library" N="197" UNIT="leaf">

<HEAD>&para; Incipit Speculum Sancti Edmundi Cantuarensis Archipiscopi in
Anglicis. <NOTE ID="n5"><HI REND="i">Verbis</HI> understood.</NOTE></HEAD><HEAD>Here begynnys The Myrrour of Seynt Edmonde &thorn;e Ersebechope of
Canterberye.</HEAD>



<P>VIDETE vocacionem vestram. This wordes, sayse Saynte Paule in his
pisty&llbar;, and thay are thus meki&llbar; to saye one ynglysche,
`Seese &yogh;owre callynge.'  This worde falles ti&llbar; vs folke of
religiou&ntail;: and &thorn;at sais he, ti&llbar; excite vs ti&llbar;
perfeccyone.  And ther-fore, what houre &thorn;at I thynke of
my-selfe, one nyghte or on day, On a syde hafe I gret Ioye, and on
ano&thorn;er syde gret sorowe : &mdash; Ioy, for &thorn;e haly
religio&ntail;; sorowe and confusyo&ntail; for my febi&llbar;
conuersasione.  And &thorn;at es na wondire, for I hafe gret
encheso&ntail;.  Als &thorn;e wyese man saise in his sermo&ntail;, he
sais, `to com to Religio&ntail; es souerayne perfeccyone; and there-in
noghte perfitly to lyffe, es souerayne dampnacyone.'  And thar-for
&thorn;are es na turne of &thorn;e way bot ane, to come in
congregacyone, &thorn;at es, to drawe to perfeccione als &thorn;ou
wi&llbar; &thorn;i saluacyone, to leue a&llbar; &thorn;at es in this
worlde and a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;er-to langys, and sett thi myghte
to lyffe perfitly.  To lyffe perfitly, as Sayne Bernarde vs kennys,
&THORN;at es, to lyffe honourabilly, mekely, & lufesomly.
Honourabilly, als to God, &thorn;at &thorn;ou sett thy&ntail; Entente
to do Hys wi&llbar;, &thorn;at es [at] say in a&llbar; thynges
&thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; thynke in hert, or say with mouthe, or
doo in dede, with any of &thorn;i fyve wittes; alls with seynge of
eghe,
<PB N="17">
Herynge of Ere, Smellynge of neese, Suellynge of throtte, towchynge of
hande, Gangand, or standande, Lygand, or sittande, thynke at &thorn;e
begynnynge if &thorn;at it be Goddes wi&llbar; or noghte.  And if it
be Goddis wi&llbar;, do it at thy powere.  And if it be noghte Hys
wi&llbar;, do it noghte, for to suffre &thorn;e dede.</P>

<P>Bot now may &thorn;ou aske mee `what es Goddes wy&llbar; ?` I say
&thorn;e, His wi&llbar; es na no&thorn;er thynge bot &thorn;i
halynes. Als &thorn;e Apposti&llbar; in his pysti&llbar; : &mdash;
&para; Hec est Voluntas Dei, Sanctificacio vestra: &THORN;at es to
say, &thorn;at es Goddes wi&llbar;, &thorn;at &yogh;e be haly. Bot now
may &thorn;ou aske me: `What mase man haly ?` I say &thorn;e, twa
thynges with-owtte&ntail; ma, &thorn;at es, knaweynge and lufe.
Knaweyng of sothefastnes, and Lufe of gudnes.  Bot to &thorn;e
knaweynge of Godde, &thorn;at es sothefastnes, ne may &thorn;ou noghte
co&mtail; Bot be knaweynge of thi selfe; ne &yogh;it to &thorn;e luf
of Godde may &thorn;ou noghte co&mtail;, bet thurghe &thorn;e luf of
thyn&ntail; evy&ntail;-crysty&ntail;.  To &thorn;e knaweyng of
&thorn;i selfe may &thorn;ou co&mtail; with besy vmby- thynkynge; And
to &thorn;e knaweynge of Godde thurghe pure contemplacionne.  To
&thorn;e knaweynge of &thorn;i selfe &thorn;ou may co&mtail; o&ntail;
&thorn;is manere: Thynke besely and ofte what &thorn;ou erte, what
&thorn;ou was, and what &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be.  Fyrste, als vn-to
&thorn;i body: &thorn;ou erte now vylere &thorn;a&ntail; any mukke;
&thorn;ou was gety&ntail; of sa vile imatire and sa gret fylt&hbar;e,
&thorn;at it es schame for to nevyn&ntail;, and abhomynacyo&ntail; for
to thynke; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be delyuerde to tades and to neddyrs
for to ete.  What &thorn;ou has bene and what thow erte, now sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou als to &thorn;i saule, thynke, For what &thorn;ou<MILESTONE
N="197 bk." UNIT="leaf"> sa&llbar;
be &thorn;ou may noghte wyete nowe.  Vmbethynke &thorn;e nowe how
&thorn;ou has dn&ntail; gret sy&nmacr;s and many, and how thou has
lefte gret gudnes and many.  Thynke how lange &thorn;ou hase lyffede,
and what thow has rescheyuede, and how &thorn;ou has dyspende it.  For
ilke an houre &thorn;at &thorn;ou has noghte thoghte one Godde,
&thorn;ou has it tynte.  For &thorn;ou sa&llbar; &yogh;elde resonne of
ilke-ane ydi&llbar; thoghte, of ilke-ane ydi&llbar; dede, of ilke-ane
ydi&llbar; worde.  And righte as &thorn;ou has noghte ane hare of thi
heuede &thorn;at it ne sa&llbar; be gloryfyede, if swa be &thorn;ou be
safede, Righte swa sa&llbar; eschape nane houre &thorn;at it ne
sa&llbar; [be] accountede.  A Ihesu, mercy ! If a&llbar; &thorn;is
worlde ware fu&llbar; of
 
<!-- 0010.p18-19.txt -->
<PB N="18">

sma&llbar;e powdire, wha sulde be sa qwaynte &thorn;at he sulde or
moghte Iugge ilke a thoghte, ilke a sawe, ilke a dede by
&thorn;a&mtail; selfe, and twy&ntail; ilke ane fra o&thorn;er? Certis
na thynge bot &thorn;e saule, &thorn;at es a thowsande sythes gretter
&thorn;an a&llbar; &thorn;is worlde, if it ware a thowsande sythes
gretter &thorn;an it es.  And it es so fu&llbar; of dyuerse thoghtes,
lykynges and &yogh;ernynges, wha moghte &thorn;an thus seke his herte
&thorn;at he moght knawe a&llbar; &thorn;at es &thorn;are-in or thynke
it ? See nowe, my dere hertly frende, howe &thorn;ou has gret nede of
knawynge of thi selfe.  Sythe&ntail; aftyrwarde take gude hede whate
&thorn;ou erte nowe, als vn-to &thorn;i saule; howe &thorn;ow has
litty&llbar; of gude in the, and litti&llbar; of witte and
litti&llbar; of powere; For &thorn;ou &yogh;ernys ilke a daye
&thorn;at at noghte avayles the, and euer mare ouer lattly &thorn;at
at may availe the.  Dere frende, &thorn;ou erte dessayfede sa ofte
with vayne Ioye; nowe trauelde with drede, nowe erte &thorn;ou lyftede
one lofte with false trayste.  See now on &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde :
&mdash; &THORN;ou ert chaungeabi&llbar;: &thorn;at at &thorn;ou
wi&llbar; doo to day, &thorn;ou wi&llbar; noghte to morne.  And ofte
sythes &thorn;ou erte anoyede eftire many thynges, and turment if
&thorn;ou hafe thaym noghte.  And sythen when &thorn;ou has
&thorn;a&mtail; at &thorn;i wi&llbar;, &thorn;an erte &thorn;ou of
thaa thynges annoyede.  Thynke &yogh;itt one &thorn;e to&thorn;er
syde, how &thorn;ou erte lyghte to fande, frele to agaynestande, and
redy to assente.  Off a&llbar; &thorn;ese wrechidnes now has &thorn;e
delyuerde Ihesu &thorn;i spouse, and delyuers &thorn;e ylke day mare
and mare.  For whe&ntail; &thorn;ou was noghte, He mad &thorn;e in
saule aftire His awe&ntail; lyknesse and His ymage, and &thorn;i body
made of foule stynkande sky&umacr;&mmacr; of &thorn;e erthe, whare-of
es abhomynacyone to thynke, He mad &thorn;e in witte and in membirs sa
nobi&llbar; and sa faire &thorn;at nane ca&ntail; deuyse.  Thynke now
besyly, &yogh;e &thorn;at has fleschely frendis and kynredy&ntail;,
why &yogh;e luffe &thorn;a&mtail; sa derely and sa tendirly. If
&thorn;ou say &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes &thorn;i fadire or &thorn;i
modire for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ou ert of &thorn;aire blude and of
flesche gety&ntail;, Sa are &thorn;e wormes &thorn;at comes of
&thorn;a&mtail; day be day.  On a-no&thorn;er syde &thorn;ou has
no&thorn;er of &thorn;a&mtail; body ne saule, Bot &thorn;ou &thorn;an
has of God thurghe thay&mtail;.  For whate sulde &thorn;ou hafe bene
if &thorn;ou had duellyde swilke as &thorn;ou was of thay&mtail;, when
&thorn;ou genderide in fylthe and in sy&ntail; ? One &thorn;e
to&thorn;er syd, if &thorn;ou lufe brethire or
<PB N="19">
systers or o&thorn;er kynredy&ntail;, for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ay are
of &thorn;e same flesche of fadir or of modire, and of &thorn;aire
blude, by &thorn;e same sky&llbar; solde &thorn;ou lufe a pece of
&thorn;aire flesche if it [ware] schorne a-waye; and &thorn;at solde
be errour gret with-owtte&ntail; mesure.  &yogh;yfe &thorn;ou say
&thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes &thorn;am for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe
fleschely fegure in lyknes of ma&ntail;, and for-thy &thorn;at
&thorn;ay <MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="leaf"> haue saule ryghte als &thorn;ou has, &thorn;an es
&thorn;i bro&thorn;er fleschely na nerre &thorn;an ano&thorn;er; bot
in als meki&llbar; als &thorn;ou and he hase bathe a fadire and a
modire fleschely, The begynnynge of &thorn;i flesehe, &thorn;at es, a
lytti&llbar; filt&hbar;, stynkande and fu&llbar; to see.  Thare-fore
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; lufe Hym of whaym a&llbar; &thorn;i fairenes
commes.  And &thorn;ou sa&llbar; lufe gastely ilk a man, and flee fra
now-forthwarde to lufe flesc&hbar;ly.</P>

<P>And swa sall &thorn;ou doo certaynly if &thorn;ou conabilly thynke
of gudes &thorn;at He has done gudly for &thorn;e; and mare sall doo
if &thorn;ou lufe Hym enterely; For, als I saide at &thorn;e
begynnynge, &mdash; when &thorn;ou was noghte, He made &thorn;e of noghte;
and when &thorn;ou was tynte, He fande &thorn;e; and whe&ntail;
&thorn;ou was peryschede, He soghte &thorn;e; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ou
was saulde with sy&ntail;, &thorn;an He boghte &thorn;e; and
whe&ntail; &thorn;ou was dampnede, &thorn;an He sauede &thorn;e.  And
whe&ntail; &thorn;ou was borne in sy&ntail;, He bapty&yogh;ede
&thorn;e; and sythe&ntail; aftirwarde, whe&ntail; &thorn;ou synnede sa
foully and sa ofte, &thorn;an He sufferde &thorn;e so frely, and
habade thynne amendemente sa lange, and sythe&ntail; rescheyuede
&thorn;e sa swetly, and &thorn;e has sett in sa swete a falachipe.
And ilke a day when &thorn;ou mysdose, &thorn;an He reprofes &thorn;e;
and whe&ntail; &thorn;ou repentis &thorn;e, &thorn;an He forgyffes
the; and when &thorn;ou erris, &thorn;an He amendis &thorn;e; and when
&thorn;ou dredis &thorn;e, &thorn;an He leris &thorn;e; and wbe&ntail;
&thorn;ou hungers, &thorn;an He fedis &thorn;e; and when &thorn;ou
erte calde, &thorn;a&ntail; He warmes &thorn;e; and whe&ntail;
&thorn;ou has hete, &thorn;an He kelis &thorn;e; and when &thorn;ou
slepis, &thorn;an He saues &thorn;e; and whe&ntail; &thorn;ou rysez
vpe, &thorn;an He vphaldes &thorn;e; and euer-mare when &thorn;ou erte
at male eese, &thorn;an He comforthes &thorn;e.  Thyre gudnes, and
many o&thorn;er, hase done vnto &thorn;e thi swete spouse Ihesu
Criste.  And &thorn;e swettnes of His herte sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke
euer-mare, and euer speke &thorn;are-of, and euer-mare lofe Hym, and
euer thanke Hym, and that bathe nyghte & day, if &thorn;ou oghte
ka&ntail; of lufe.</P>

<P>And &thorn;are-for, when &thorn;ou ryses of &thorn;i bedde at morne
or at
 
<!-- 0011.p20-21.txt -->
<PB N="20">


mydnyghte, thynke als tite how many thowsand me&ntail; & wome&ntail;
ere perischede in body or in saule &thorn;at nyghte: Some in fyre,
Some in o&thorn;er manere, als in water or one lande; Some robbide,
woundide, Slayne, dede sodanly with-owtty&ntail; sacramentis, and
fally&ntail; in-ti&llbar; dampnacione ay lastande.  Thynk alswa how
many thowsande &thorn;at nyghte are in peri&llbar; of saule, &thorn;at
es to say, in dedly sy&ntail;, als in glotony, lechery, Couetyse, in
manes-slaynge, and in many o&thorn;er folyes.  And of a&llbar;
&thorn;ise i&llbar;es, the has delyuered thy swete Lorde Ihesu,
with-owtte&ntail; &thorn;i deserte.  What seruyce hase &thorn;ou
donne, whare-fore He hase &thorn;usgate keped &thorn;e, and many
o&thorn;er loste and forsake&ntail; ? For sothe, if &thorn;ou take gud
kepe how gret gude He has done &thorn;e on ilk a syde, &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; fynd hym ocupiede aboute &thorn;i profet, als He did
na&ntail; o&thorn;er thynge, bot anely ware entendande to &thorn;e and
to &thorn;i hele, als if He had forgety&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;is
worlde for to be anely intendan&dtail; vn-to &thorn;e.  &para; And
when &thorn;ou hase &thorn;is thoghte, lyfte vpe thi handis and thanke
thi Lorde of &thorn;is and of a&llbar;<MILESTONE N="198 bk." UNIT="leaf"> o&thorn;er gudes, and say one
&thorn;is manere, `My <NOTE ID="n6">These prayers are first given in the MS. in Latin &mdash;Gracias tibi ... In manus tuas...&mdash;the translation immediately following. It did not seem necessary to print the Latin as well, the English being a full equivalent. The translation in the first case is introduced with the words 'This Oryso&ntail; es &thorn;us to say one Inglysche my Lorde,' &amp;c.; and in the second 'And &thorn;is orysone es &thorn;us mekill to saye Lorde' &amp;c.</NOTE> Lorde Ihesu Criste ! grace I &yogh;elde, and
thanke &thorn;e, &thorn;at me, thyne vnworthy seruande, &thorn;ou hase
kepid couerde and vesete in &thorn;is nyghte (Or in &thorn;is day),
hale, safe, and wemles vn-to &thorn;is ty&mtail; &thorn;ou hase made
to come, and for a&llbar; o&thorn;er gudes and benefitis &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase geffy&ntail; me, anely thurghe &thorn;i gudnes and
&thorn;i pete, &thorn;ou &thorn;at lyffes and regnes endles.
Ame&ntail;.'  Dere frende, in &thorn;is same manere sall &thorn;ou say
when &thorn;ou rysez at morne, and when &thorn;ou lygges dow&ntail; at
evy&ntail;.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ou has done swa, &thorn;an
sa&llbar; &thorn;ou besyly thynke how &thorn;ou hase spende &thorn;at
day (or &thorn;at nyghte), and pray Go&dtail; of mercy of &thorn;e
i&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou hase done, and of &thorn;e gude &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase lefte vn-ti&llbar; &thorn;at ty&mtail;.  And, dere
frende, do na thynge in &thorn;is lyfe ti&llbar; &thorn;ou commend
&thorn;i selfe, and thi frendes qwykke and dede, in the handis of thi
swete Lorde Ihesu Criste, and say one &thorn;is maner, `Lorde Ihesu
Criste! in
<PB N="21">
&thorn;i handis, and in &thorn;e handis of thy&ntail; haly
Ange&llbar;s, I gyffe in &thorn;is nyghte (or in &thorn;is day) my
saule and my body, my Fadir and my Modire, my brothire and my systirs,
frendis and seruandes, neghtburs and kynredy&ntail;, my gude-doers,
and a&llbar; folke righte trowande.  Kepe vs, Lorde, in &thorn;is
nyghte (or &thorn;is day) thurg&hbar; &thorn;e gud dedis and &thorn;e
prayere of &thorn;e blyssed mayde&ntail; Marie and a&llbar; thi
halous, fra vices and fra wykked &yogh;ernyngez, fra synns and fra
fandynges of &thorn;e deue&llbar;, fra sodayne and avysede dede, and
fra &thorn;e paynes of helle.  Lyght my herte of the Haly Gaste and of
thi haly grace! Lorde! &thorn;ou make me to be bouxsome euer-mare to
&thorn;i byddynges, and suffire me neuer mare to twy&ntail; fra the,
endles Ihesu, Lorde in Trinite!  Amen!'  My dere frende, if &thorn;ou
hase &thorn;is manere, &thorn;an sa&llbar; &thorn;ou hafe verray
knaweynge of thi selfe, For thus saise haly Writte, `If &thorn;ou<MILESTONE
N="199" UNIT="leaf">
trayste one thy selfe, to &thorn;i selfe &thorn;ou sa&llbar; be
taky&ntail;; and &yogh;if &thorn;ou trayste one Gode and noghte one
&thorn;i-selfe, to God &thorn;ou sa&llbar;bhe gyffe&ntail;.'  And
&thorn;is maner of consederatyone es callede 'medytacyone,' For by
&thorn;is maner of knawynge of &thorn;i selfe, & by &thorn;is maner of
medytacyone, sa&llbar; &thorn;ou come to &thorn;e knaweynge of Gode,
by haly contemplacyone.</P>

<P>Wiet &thorn;ou &thorn;at &thorn;are es thre manere of
contemplacyone.  The fyrste es in creaturs.  The to&thorn;er es in
haly scripture.  The thirde es in Gode hym-selfe in His nature.  Thow
sa&llbar; wyet &thorn;at contemplacyone es na no&thorn;er thynge bot
thoghte of Godde in gret lykynge in saule, And to se His gudnes in His
creaturs.  His gudnes in His creaturs may &thorn;ou see one &thorn;is
manere.  Thre thynges pryncypaly ere in Gode, &thorn;at es to say,
Myghte, Wysdome, and gudnes.  Myghte es appropirde to Godd &thorn;e
Fadire. Wysdome, to God &thorn;e So&ntail;.  Gudnes, to God &thorn;e
Haly Gaste. Thurg&hbar; Goddes myghte ere a&llbar; thynges made, and
thurg&hbar; His wysdome ere a&llbar; thynges meruailously ordaynede;
and thurg&hbar; His gudnes ilke a day ere a&llbar; thynges waxande.
His powere may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire gretnes and by thaire
makynge; His wysdo&mtail; by &thorn;aire fairenes of&thorn;aire
ordaynynge; His gudnes may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire Encressynge.
&THORN;aire gretnes may &thorn;ou see by &thorn;aire four partynges,
&thorn;at es to saye, by &thorn;aire heghte, and by
 
<!-- 0012.p22-23.txt -->
<PB N="22">


&thorn;aire depnes, and by &thorn;aire largenes, and by paire lenghe.
His wysdo&mtail; may &thorn;ou see if &thorn;ou take kepe how He hase
gyffe&ntail; to ylke a creature to be.  Some He hase gyffe&ntail; to
be anely, with-owtte&ntail; mare, als vn-to stanes.  Ti&llbar;
o&thorn;er to be & to lyffe, als to grysse and trees. Ti&llbar;
o&thorn;er to be, to lyffe, to fele, als to bestes.  Ti&llbar;
o&thorn;er to be, to lyffe, to fele, and with resone to deme, als to
mane and to ange&llbar;s For stanes erre, bot &thorn;ay ne hafe nogte
lyffe, ne felys noghte, ne demes noghte.  Trees are; &thorn;ay lyffe,
Bot thay fele noghte.  Me&ntail; are; &thorn;ay lyffe, &THORN;ey fele,
and &thorn;ay deme, and &thorn;ay erre with stanes, [&thorn;ay] lyffe
with trees, &thorn;ay fele with bestes, and demys with
ange&llbar;s. Here sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke besyly &thorn;e
worthynes of manes kynde, how it ouer-passes ilke a creature. And
&thorn;are-fore saise Saynt Austy&ntail;, `I wald noghte hafe &thorn;e
stede of ane ange&llbar;e, if I myghte hafe &thorn;e stede &thorn;at
es purvayede to ma&ntail;.'  Thynk also &thorn;at ma&ntail; es worthy
gret schenchipe &thorn;at will noghte lyffe eftyre hys degre and
eftyre his condicyone askis; For a&llbar; &thorn;e creaturs in
&thorn;e worlde ere made anely for ma&ntail;.  &THORN;ase &thorn;at
ere meke, ere made for thre skylles; For to helpe vs at trauayle, als
nate, Oxe&ntail;, kye and horse; For to couer vs & clet&hbar;e vs, als
lyne, and wolle and lethire; for to fede vs and vphalde vs, als
bestes, Corne of &thorn;e ert&hbar;e, Fysche of &thorn;e See; and
&thorn;e noyande creaturs, als i&llbar; trees and venemous bestes,
&thorn;e wylke are made for thre thynges, For euro chastyyng, for oure
amendement, and for euro kennynge.  We ere chastied and puneschet,
when we ere hurte.  And &thorn;at es gret mercy of Godde, &thorn;at He
wi&llbar; chasty vs bodyly &thorn;at we be noghte punescht lastandly.
<MILESTONE N="199 bk." UNIT="leaf">We erre amendid whe&ntail; we thynke &thorn;at a&llbar; &thorn;ese ere
broghte vs for oure sy&ntail;.  For whe&ntail; we see &thorn;at sa
lytti&llbar; creaturs may noye vs, &thorn;a&ntail; we thynke one oure
wrechidnes, and &thorn;a&ntail; we ere mekyde.  We ere Eftir- warde
kende, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at we see in &thorn;ise creaturs &thorn;e
wondirfu&llbar; werkes of God oure Makere.  For mare vs availes
ti&llbar; oure ensampi&llbar; and Edifycacione, &thorn;e werkes of
&thorn;e pyssmowre &thorn;an dose &thorn;e strenghe of &thorn;e lyone
or of &thorn;e bere.  Als-swa, righte als I haue said of bestes, reght
swa vndirstande of trees; and when &thorn;ou hase donne on &thorn;is
manere, Raise vp thy herte vn-ti&llbar;
<PB N="23">
God&dtail;, and thynke how it es grete myghte to make a&llbar; thynges
of noghte, and to gyffe &thorn;am to bee, and grete wysdo&mtail; to
ordayne &thorn;am in sa gret fairenes, and in swa gret bounte, to
multyply &thorn;a&mtail; ilk a day for oure prowe.  A! mercy
God&dtail;! how we are vnkynde! We dyspende a&llbar; His creaturs, and
He &thorn;am makes !  We confound &thorn;a&mtail;, and He
&thorn;a&mtail; gouernes.  We distruy &thorn;a&mtail; ilke a day, and
He &thorn;am multyplies.  And &thorn;are-fore say ti&llbar; Hym in thi
herte, `Lorde ! for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte, &thorn;ay ere,
and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte fayre, &thorn;ay are faire ;
and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ou arte gude, &thorn;ay are gude.
With gud ryghte &thorn;ay loue &thorn;e, and Onoures &thorn;e, and
gloryfyes &thorn;e, a&llbar; thy creatures.  O blyssed Godd in
Trinyte! with gud ryghte &thorn;ay loue &thorn;e for &thorn;aire
gudnes, with gud ryghte &thorn;ay anoure&ntail; &thorn;e for thaire
fairenes, with gud righte &thorn;ay glorifye &thorn;e for &thorn;aire
profet, a&llbar; &thorn;i creaturs, blyssed Trinyte !  Of wha&mtail;
a&llbar; thynges ere thurg&hbar; His powere made; Thu[r]g&hbar; whaym
a&llbar; thynges are thurg&hbar; Hys wysdo&mtail; gouernede; In whaym
a&llbar; thynges are thurg&hbar; His bounte multipliede; Ti&llbar; Hym
honour and louynge with-owte&ntail; [ende].  Ame&ntail; !'</P>

<P>&THORN;E to&thorn;er degre of contemplacyone es in Haly Wryte. Bot
nowe may &thorn;ou say to me, `I &thorn;at knawes na letters, how may
I euer mare com to contemplacyone of Haly Writte ?'  Now, my dere
frende, vndirstande me swetely, and I sa&llbar; say perchance to
&thorn;e a&llbar; &thorn;at es wrete&ntail;, if &thorn;ou ka&ntail;
noghte vndirstand Haly Writt.  Here gladly &thorn;e gud &thorn;at
me&ntail; saise &thorn;e: and whe&ntail; &thorn;ou heres Haly Wryte,
ow&thorn;er in sermo&ntail; or in priue collacyone, take kepe als
tyte, if &thorn;ou here oghte &thorn;at may availe &thorn;e ti&llbar;
edyfycacyo&ntail;, to hate sy&ntail; and to lufe vertue, and to dowte
payne, and to &yogh;erne Ioye, To dispyse &thorn;is worlde, and to hye
to blysse, and whate &thorn;ou sa&llbar; doo and whate &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; lefe, and a&llbar; &thorn;at lyghtes &thorn;inne
vndirstandynge in knawynge of sothefastnes, and a&llbar; &thorn;at
kyndi&llbar;s &thorn;i lykynge in brynnynge of charite; For of
&thorn;ise twa gudnes, es a&llbar; &thorn;at es wrety&ntail; in preue
or in apperte.  Owte of haly writte sall &thorn;ou drawe and cu&ntail;
witte, whilke are &thorn;e seue&ntail; dedly synnes, and &thorn;e
seue&ntail; vertus, and &thorn;e ten <MILESTONE N="200" UNIT="leaf">comandmentis, and &thorn;e tuelfe
artycles of &thorn;e trout&hbar;e, and &thorn;e seue&ntail;
sacramentis of Haly Kyrke and &thorn;e
 
<!-- 0013.p24-25.txt -->
<PB N="24">


seue&ntail; gyftis of &thorn;e Haly Gaste, and &thorn;e seue&ntail;
werkes of mercy, and &thorn;e seue&ntail; vertuz of &thorn;e
Gospe&llbar;, and &thorn;e seuen prayers of &thorn;e pater noster.</P>

<P>&THORN;ir are &thorn;e seue&ntail; dedly synnes : &mdash; </P>

<P>Pryde and Envy, Ire, Slout&hbar;, Couetyse, Glotony and Lechery.
Pryde es lufe of vnkyndly heghyng; and &thorn;ar-of comes &thorn;ir
seuen vnbouxomnes agayne God, or agayne souerayngne, &thorn;at es to
say, to lefe &thorn;at &thorn;at es commandyd, and to do &thorn;at
that es defendyde.  The to&thorn;er branc&hbar; of pride es surquytry,
&thorn;at es, to vndirtake thyng ouer his powere, or wenys to be mare
wyse &thorn;an he es, or better &thorn;an he es, and auauntez hym of
gude &thorn;at he hase of o&thorn;er, or of i&llbar; &thorn;at he hase
of hym-selfe.  The thrid braunche of pride es ypocrisye, &thorn;at es,
whe&ntail; he feynys hym to hafe gudnes &thorn;at he hase noghte, and
hydes &thorn;e wykkednes &thorn;at he hase.  The fert&hbar;
braunc&hbar; of pride es despyte of thyne euencriste&ntail;, &thorn;at
es, when man lesses gudnes of o&thorn;er, for-thi &thorn;at hym selfe
suld seme &thorn;e bettir.  The fyfte braunche, &thorn;at es, when man
makes lyknes be-twyx his awe&ntail; wykkednes and o&thorn;er mens
wikkednes, &thorn;at his awe&ntail; may seme &thorn;e lesse.  The
sexte braunche of Pryde es vnschamefulnes, &thorn;at es, when men hase
noghte schame of i&llbar; ded aperte.  The seue&ntail; braunche of
pryde es Elacio&ntail;, &thorn;at es, when a man hase heghe herte,
&thorn;at he wi&llbar; no&yogh;te suffire to felawe ne mayster.  Dere
frende, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wit &thorn;at thre thynges ere, whare-of a
man Enprides hym, &thorn;at es to say, of &thorn;e gudez &thorn;at he
hase of kynde, als fairenes or streng&hbar;e or of gude witte or of
nobi&llbar;e kynredy&ntail;.  The to&thorn;er thyng es &thorn;ait men
hase of purchase, als cunnynge, Grace, gud loos, or dygnyte or offyce.
The thirde thynge es erthely thynge or erthely gude, als clethynge,
houssynge, Rentez, Possessio&ntail;, Men&yogh;e, horssyng, and honour
of &thorn;is worlde.  Pride makes man to be of gret herte and heghe,
to despyse his euencriste&ntail;, and to &yogh;erne heghenes and
maystry ouer o&thorn;er.  The to&thorn;er dedly sy&ntail; es `Envy.'
And &thorn;at es, Ioye of o&thorn;er mens harme, and sorowe of
o&thorn;er mens wele-fare.  And &thorn;at may be in herte with
lykynge, or in mout&hbar; with bakbyttynge, or in werke with of mens
gudnes wythdrawyng, or e&llbar;s with i&llbar; procurynge.
<PB N="25">


Envye mase man to hafe &thorn;e herte hevy of &thorn;at he sese
o&thorn;er men mare worthi &thorn;an he in any thyng.  The third dedly
sy&ntail; es `wret&hbar;e,' &thorn;at es, ane vnresonaby&llbar;
temperoure of herte; and of it comes stryfes and contekes
schamefu&llbar;, and dyuerse wordes, and deuyouse and wikked
sclandirs.  <MILESTONE N="200 bk." UNIT="leaf">The fert&hbar;e dedly sy&ntail; es `slouthe;' and
&thorn;at mase manes herte hevy and slawe in gude dede, and makes
ma&ntail; to yrke in prayere or halynes, and puttes man in wykkednes
of wanhope, for it slokyns &thorn;e lykynge of gastely lufe.  &para;
The fyfte dedly sy&ntail; es `couetyse,' and &thorn;at es, ane
vn-mesurabi&llbar; luffe to hafe erthely gudes; and it destroyes &
blyndes manes herte.  And &thorn;are-of commes tresones, False athes,
wykked reste, Malice, and hardnes of herte agaynes mercy.  &para; The
sexte dedly sy&ntail; es `glotony;' and &thorn;at makes ma&ntail; to
serue and to be bouxome ti&llbar; wykked lykynges of &thorn;e
flesc&hbar;e, &thorn;e whilke man suld maister and ouercome with
mesure.  Of glotony commes vayne Ioy, lyghtnes, and litti&llbar;
vndirstandynge.  &para; The seue&ntail; dedly sy&ntail; es `lecherye;'
and &thorn;at mase manes herte to melte, and to playe thare &thorn;are
his herte lykes, and heldes, and &thorn;at with-owte&ntail; gouernynge
of resoune.  Of lechery commes blyndynge of herte, in prayere
vnstabilnes and fulle hastynes, lufe of hym selfe, hatrede&ntail; of
Godde, lufe of &thorn;is worlde, vgglynes, and whanhope of &thorn;e
blysse of heue&ntail;.  &para; Dere frende, thire are &thorn;e
seue&ntail; dedly synnes; and wele ere &thorn;ay callid dedly synnes,
For Pride twynnes fra man his Godde, Envy his euencriste&ntail;, Ire
hym-selfe twynnes, Slouthe hym tourmentes, Couetyse hym be-gyles,
Glotony hym dessayues, and Lecherye hym in thraledome settis.</P>

<P>Nowe hase &thorn;ou herde &thorn;e seue&ntail; sekenes of manes
saule.  &para; Sythe&ntail; aftirwarde commes &thorn;e souerayne
leche, and takes &thorn;ere medcynes, and waresche ma&ntail; of
&thorn;ese seue&ntail; seknes, and stabi&llbar;s hym in &thorn;e
seue&ntail; vertus&yogh;, thurg&hbar; &thorn;e gyftes of &thorn;e Haly
Gaste.  &THORN;e whilke are &thorn;ese, &para; &thorn;e gaste of
wysdom and vndirstandynge, &thorn;e gaste of consaile and of
stalworthenes, &thorn;e gaste of cunnynge and of pete, and &thorn;e
gaste of drede of Godde Almyghty. Thurghe &thorn;ese gyftes oure Lord
Ihesu lerres ma&ntail; a&llbar; &thorn;at he hase myster ti&llbar;
&thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es callid actyfe, and til &thorn;e lyfe called
contem-


 
<!-- 0014.p26-27.txt -->
<PB N="26">


platyfe.  And se howe firste, ma&ntail; suld lefe &thorn;e euy&llbar;
and do &thorn;e gude: lefe &thorn;e euy&llbar;, &thorn;at teches vs
&thorn;e gaste of drede of Godd Almyghty; and do &thorn;e gude,
[&thorn;at] leres vs &thorn;e gaste of pete.  And for-&thorn;i
&thorn;at twa thynges are &thorn;at lettis vs to do gude, that es at
saye, wele-fare and tribulacione of &thorn;is worlde; For wele-fare
desayues vs with losengery, tribulacio&ntail; with hardnes of noyes &
dysses; for-&thorn;i sa&llbar; &thorn;ou despyse &thorn;e wele-fare of
&thorn;is worlde, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be noghte &thorn;er-with
dessayued; and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e &thorn;e gaste of cunnynge;
and &thorn;ou sa&llbar; stallwort&hbar;ly suffire tribulacyo&ntail;,
&thorn;at &thorn;ou be noghte ouercomme&ntail; ; and &thorn;at teches
vs &thorn;e gaste of stallworthenes.  And &thorn;ire foure suffice
ti&llbar; &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es callid actyfe.  And &thorn;e
to&thorn;er thre fallys to &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;at es callid
contemplatyfe, <MILESTONE N="201" UNIT="leaf">For thre maners of contemplacio&ntail;.  Ane es in
creaturs; and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e gaste of vndirstandynge.  The
to&thorn;er es in Haly Writte, whare &thorn;ou sese whatte &thorn;ou
doo & what &thorn;ou sa&llbar; lefe, and &thorn;at leres &thorn;e the
gaste of consaile.  The thirde manere es in Godde Hym-selfe ; and
&thorn;at leres vs &thorn;e gaste of wysdo&mtail;.  Now &thorn;ou sese
thurg&hbar; &thorn;e gyftes of Ihesu, how He es besy abowte oure hele.
Eftire &thorn;is sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wiete whilke ere &thorn;e
te&ntail; comandementis.  &para; &THORN;e firste comandement es
&thorn;is, `Thow sa&llbar; wirchippe bot a Godde, &thorn;i Lorde, and
ti&llbar; Hym anely &thorn;ou sa&llbar; serue.'  &THORN;at es at say,
wyrchipe Hym with righte trout&hbar;e, Serue vnti&llbar; anely with
gude werkes.  Here sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke if &thorn;ou hafe lelly
serued Godde & wirchiped Godde; if &thorn;ou hafe seruede Hym ouer
a&llbar; thynge, if &thorn;ou hafe &yogh;olden Hym &thorn;at that
&thorn;ou hyghte, or if &thorn;ou hafe done lesse penance, and if
&thorn;ou hafe &yogh;oldy&ntail; Hym &thorn;at that &thorn;ou hyghte
Hym in &thorn;i cristyndo&mtail;, That was, to forsake &thorn;e
deue&llbar;e and a&llbar; his werkes, and in God lelly to trowe.  And
thurg&hbar;e &thorn;is commandement es ma&ntail; ordaynede ynence God
&thorn;e Fadire.  &para; &THORN;e to&thorn;er commandement es defendid
to take Goddes name in vayne; and lying and falsenes &thorn;are-in es
defendi&dtail;; and thurg&hbar;e &thorn;is commandement es man
ordaynede ynence God&dtail; &thorn;e So&ntail;, &thorn;at saise
Hym-selfe `I am sothefastnes.'  &para; &THORN;e thirde commandemente
es, `vmbythynke &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou kepe &thorn;e
haly-dayes,' &thorn;at es to saye, in &thorn;ine awe&ntail; herte, to
kepe &thorn;e in riste and pees with-owtte&ntail; seruage of sy&ntail;
or of bodyly
<PB N="27">


dedis.  And &thorn;is commandement ordaynes ma&ntail; to reschayfe
&thorn;e Haly Gaste.  &THORN;ise thre commandmentes lerres ma&ntail;
howgates he sa&llbar; hafe hym ynence God&dtail; &thorn;e Trynite, to
whas lyknes he es made in saule.  &THORN;e o&thorn;er seue&ntail;
commandementes leres man how he sa&llbar; hafe hym ynence his
euencriste&ntail;.  &para; &THORN;e firste es, `&thorn;ou sa&llbar;
honour &thorn;i fadire and &thorn;i modire fleschely and gastely, and
&thorn;at in twa maners, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be
bouxom to thaym in reuerence and honour, and &thorn;ou helpe
&thorn;a&mtail; at thy powere in a&llbar; thynges &thorn;at &thorn;ay
hafe myster, &thorn;at &thorn;ou be of lange lyfe in erthe; For if
&thorn;ou wi&llbar; be of lange lyfe, it es reso&ntail; &thorn;at
&thorn;ou honoure thay&mtail; of whaym &thorn;ou hase &thorn;e lyfe;
For he &thorn;at wi&llbar; noghte honoure hym thurg&hbar; whaym he es,
it es noghte righte &thorn;at he be mare &thorn;an he es.  &para;
&THORN;e to&thorn;er commandement es &thorn;is, `&THORN;ou sa&llbar;
sla na man.'  Here sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wyt &thorn;at slaughter es of
many maneres.  For &thorn;er es manes-slaghter of hand, of tunge, of
herte.  Mannes-slaynge of hande es when a ma&ntail; slaes ano&thorn;er
with his handez, or when he duse hym in bandis of dede, als in
preso&ntail; or in o&thorn;er stede &thorn;at may be encheso&ntail; of
his dede.  Manes-slaynge of tunge es in twa maners, thurghe
commandement, or thurg&hbar;e enticement.  Manes-slayng of herte es
alswa one twa maners, &thorn;at es, whe&ntail; me&ntail; &yogh;ernys
and couaytes ded of o&thorn;er, and when he suffyrs man to dy, <MILESTONE
N="201 bk." UNIT="leaf">and
wi&llbar; noghte delyuer hym if &hbar;e hafe powere.  &para; &THORN;e
thirde commandement es &thorn;is: `&THORN;ou sa&llbar; do na lechery;'
and &thorn;at es ryghte. Wha-sa wi&llbar; hafe &thorn;e lyfe
with-owtte&ntail; corupcyone in &thorn;e Ioy of heue&ntail;, hym
byhoues kepe his lyfe &thorn;at es dedly, with-owtte&ntail; corupcione
of body.  &para; The ferthe commandement es &thorn;is, `&THORN;ou
sa&llbar; do na thyfte ne na falsenes;' and &thorn;at es ryghte.  For
he &thorn;at wi&llbar; safe o&thorn;er menes lyfe, he sa&llbar; noghte
do away &thorn;at that moghte his lyfe sustayne.  &para; The fyfte
commandement es &thorn;is, ` &THORN;ou sa&llbar; noghte bere false
wittnes agaynes thyne euencristy&ntail; wit&hbar; hym &thorn;at
wi&llbar; noye hym or sla hym.'  And &thorn;at es ryghte; For he
&thorn;at wi&llbar; noghte sckathe his euencristy&ntail;, he sa&llbar;
noghte consente, ne na consaile gyffe, to do hym i&llbar;.  &para;
&THORN;e sexte commandement and &thorn;e seuen&dtail; er &thorn;ir,
`&THORN;ou sa&llbar; noghte couaite &thorn;i neghtboure wyfe, ne
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; noghte couaite his
 
<!-- 0015.p28-29.txt -->
<PB N="28">


house, ne nane of his gude wrangwysly,' For he &thorn;at hase wykked
wi&llbar; and i&llbar; Entente in his herte, he may noghte lang
with-haldynge hym fra wykkide dede; and &thorn;er-fore, if &thorn;ou
wi&llbar; noghte do lecherye, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; noghte consente to
ma&ntail; ne to woma&ntail; &thorn;at it duse; and if &thorn;ou
wi&llbar; noghte stele, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; noghte couayte o&thorn;er
mennes thynges in &thorn;i herte.  Dere frende, &thorn;ir are &thorn;e
ten commandementes &thorn;at God gafe ti&llbar; Moyses in the mounte
of Synay.  The thre fyrste er pertenande to &thorn;e lufe of God, and
the to&thorn;er seue&ntail; to &thorn;e lufe of &thorn;i-selfe and of
thyne eue&ntail; crysty&ntail;.</P>

<P>Now, efter, sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wyt whilke ere &thorn;e seue&ntail;
vertus&yogh;, &thorn;at es to saye &para; Trouthe, Trayste, and lufe,
Wysedo&mtail; and Rightwysenes, Mesure and Force.  Of &thorn;e same
matire er &thorn;e seue&ntail; vertus &thorn;at &thorn;e te&ntail;
commandementis, bot &thorn;is es &thorn;e varyance be-twyx thaym: The
te&ntail; commandmentis kennes vs what we sa&llbar; do, and &thorn;e
seue&ntail; vertus kennes vs how we sa&llbar; doo.  The thre fyrste,
&thorn;at es to say, Trouthe, trayste and lufe, ordaynes the how
&thorn;ou sa&llbar; lyfe als to God&dtail;: &thorn;e to&thorn;er foure
how &thorn;ou sa&llbar; ordayne thyne awe&ntail; lyfe &thorn;at
sa&llbar; lede till &thorn;e Ioye of heue&ntail;.  Dere frende, the
awe to wyt &thorn;at we ere a&llbar; made for ane En&dtail;, &thorn;at
es to say, for to knawe Godde, to hafe Hym, and to lufe Hym.  Bot thre
thynges er nedefu&llbar; at puruaye ti&llbar; oure cunnynge, That es
to wyte, whedyr we sa&llbar; ga, and &thorn;at we wy&llbar; comme
thedyre, and &thorn;at we hafe trayste to com thedyre; For grete foly
ware it to be-gy&ntail; &thorn;e thynge mane may noghte ende;
&yogh;itte, one &thorn;e to&thorn;er syde, &thorn;e mane &thorn;at
wi&llbar; wyele doo, hym nedide to hafe wysdo&mtail;, myghte, and
wi&llbar;; &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at he kon&ntail; doo, and
&thorn;at he may doo, and &thorn;at he wy&llbar; doo.  Bot
for-&thorn;i &thorn;at we hafe noghte cunnynge, myghte, ne wi&llbar;
of oure selfe, for-&thorn;i hase Godde gyfe&ntail; vs trouthe, for to
fulfi&llbar; &thorn;e defaute of oure myghte.  Sothefaste lufe es for
to ordayne oure wi&llbar; to &thorn;e tane and to &thorn;e
to&thorn;er.  Trouthe ordaynes vs to Godde &thorn;e So&ntail;, to
whay&mtail; es appropyrde Wysdo&mtail;; Trayste, ti&llbar; God&dtail;
&thorn;e Fadyre, to whaym es appropyrde myghte; Lufe, to &thorn;e Haly
Gaste, ti&llbar; whay&mtail; es appropyrde gudnes.  And &thorn;are
trouthe makes vs to hafe knawynge; and &thorn;at knaweynge vs sayse
&thorn;at He es wondyrfu&llbar;; Fre es He &thorn;at
<PB N="29">


one &thorn;is manere and &thorn;us largely gyffes of His gudnes; and
of &thorn;at comes trayste, and [of] &thorn;at knawynge, &thorn;at
sais &thorn;at He es gude Commes &thorn;e thyrde Sothefastnes,
&thorn;at es lufe, For ylke a thynge luffes kyndely &thorn;e gude.</P>

<MILESTONE N="202" UNIT="leaf"><P> Dere frende, here sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wyte whilke are &thorn;e
twelue artycles of &thorn;e trouthe.  &para; The firste es &thorn;is,
&thorn;at Godde es ane in Hym-selfe and thre in persouns,
with-owtte&ntail; begynnynge, and with-owtte&ntail; Endynge, and
&thorn;at a&llbar; thynges [were] made of noghte with His worde.
&para; &THORN;e to&thorn;er artecle es, &thorn;at Goddes so&ntail;
tuke flesche and blode of &thorn;e blyssed mayde&ntail; Marie, and was
borne of hire, sothefaste God&dtail; and sothefaste ma&ntail;. &para;
&THORN;e thirde es, &thorn;at He was dede and graue&ntail;, noghte for
nede, Bot for to by vs of His fre wi&llbar;. &para; The ferthe artecle
es, &thorn;at &thorn;e same Ihesu rase fra dede to lyfe, and we
sa&llbar; ryse alswa.  &para; The fyfte artecle es, &thorn;at &thorn;e
same Sothefaste God and ma&ntail;, steig&hbar;e vp in ti&llbar;
heue&ntail; in manhed and godhede; and we sa&llbar; steig&hbar;e vp
alswa thurg&hbar; His grace. &para; &THORN;e sext artecle es baptymme,
&thorn;at mase ma&ntail; clene of sy&ntail; &thorn;at he drawes of
kynde, and gyffes grace to clense. &para; The Seuen&dtail; artecle es
confirmacio&ntail;, &thorn;at confermys &thorn;e Haly Gaste one
ma&ntail; &thorn;at es cristenede.  &para; &THORN;e aughtened artecle
es penance, &thorn;at duse awaye a&llbar; maner of sy&ntail; dedly and
venya&llbar;.  &para; &THORN;e nynde es &thorn;e Sacrament of &thorn;e
Auter, &thorn;at confermys &thorn;e penance, and gyffes hym force
&thorn;at he fa&llbar; noghte efte in sy&ntail;, and vphaldes
hy&mtail; and reconsailles hym. &para; &THORN;e ten&dtail; artecle es
Ordyre, &thorn;at gyffes powere ti&llbar; &thorn;ay&mtail; &thorn;at
are ordeynede to do &thorn;aire Offece and to do &thorn;e sacramentis.
&para; &THORN;e elleuen&dtail; artecle es Matrimone, &thorn;at
defendis dedly sy&ntail; in werke of generacyo&ntail; by-twyx
ma&ntail; and woma&ntail;.  &para; &THORN;e twelfed artecle es
Enoyntynge, &thorn;at me&ntail; enoyntes &thorn;e seke in pere&llbar;
of dede, for alegeance of body and saule.</P>

<P>&para; Dere frende, aftyre sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wyt whilke are
&thorn;e foure vertus cardynalles, thurg&hbar; whilke a&llbar; manes
lyfe es gouernede in &thorn;is worlde, &thorn;at es, &para; Cunnynge
and Rightwisnes, Force and Mesure.  Of thir foure, saise &thorn;e Haly
Gaste in &thorn;e buke of Wysdo&mtail;, &thorn;at &thorn;are es na
thynge mare profytabi&llbar; ti&llbar; man in ert&hbar;e; and so nowe,
whare-fore, wha-sa walde any thynge wele do, firste hy&mtail; byhouys
&thorn;at he kon&ntail; chese &thorn;e i&llbar; fra &thorn;e gude, and
of twa gude, chese
 
<!-- 0016.p30-31.txt -->
<PB N="30">


&thorn;e bettire and leffe &thorn;e lesse gude; and &thorn;is es the
vertu &thorn;at es callede ryghtwysnes. <NOTE ID="n7">The description of the virtue of Prudence is here given to Righteousness or Justice, the account of which is omitted.</NOTE>  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at
twa thynges lettes ma&ntail; to do wele and lefe &thorn;e y&llbar;,
&thorn;at es at say, wele-fare of &thorn;is worlde, for it dessayfes
hy&mtail; with false vanytes; &thorn;e to&thorn;er es
tribulacyo&ntail;, to putt hym dow&ntail; with many scharpnes: agaynes
wele-fare sa&llbar; &thorn;ou hafe mesure, &thorn;at &thorn;ow be
noghte ouer hye.  And &thorn;is vertu es called `temperance.'  And
agayne aduersyte sa&llbar; &thorn;ou hafe `hardynes,' &thorn;at
&thorn;ou be noghte caste&ntail; downne.  And &thorn;at vertue es
callyde Force or streng&hbar;e.</P>

<P>&para; Here-eftyre sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wyte whylke are &thorn;e
seue&ntail; werkes of mercy. &para; The firste werke of Mercy es, to
gyffe mete to &thorn;e hunngry.  The to&thorn;er es, to gyffe drynke
to &thorn;e thrysty.  The thirde es, to clethe &thorn;e nakede.
&THORN;e ferthe es, to herbere &thorn;e herberles.  &THORN;e fyfte es,
to vesete &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at ere in prisonne.  <MILESTONE
N="202 bk." UNIT="leaf">&THORN;e sexte
es, to comfort&hbar; &thorn;e seke.  The Seuen&dtail;, to bery
&thorn;e dede.  Thyse are &thorn;e seue&ntail; werkes of mercy
&thorn;at are langande to &thorn;e body.  Bot nowe may &thorn;ou say
to me, `how sulde I, &thorn;at es in Relygyo&ntail;, and noghte hase
to gyffe at ete ne at drynke, ne clathes to &thorn;e nakede, ne
herbery to &thorn;e herberles, For I am at o&thorn;er mens wi&llbar;,
and noghte at my&ntail; awe&ntail; ? For-thi ware it better &thorn;at
I ware seculere, &thorn;at I myghte do &thorn;ise werkes of mercy.'
A, dere frende, be noghte begylede! Better it es to hafe pete and
compassione in &thorn;i herte of hym &thorn;at hase mysese and
wrechednes, Thane &thorn;ou hade a&llbar; &thorn;is werlde to gyffe
for charyte; For it es bettir wyt&hbar; compassio&ntail; to gyffe
&thorn;i-selfe als &thorn;ou erte, &thorn;an it es to gyffe &thorn;at
that &thorn;ou hase.  There-fore, dere frende, gyffe thi-selfe; and
&thorn;an gyffes &thorn;ou mare &thorn;an es in a&llbar; &thorn;is
worlde.  Bot now may &thorn;ou Say me one &thorn;is manere : &mdash;
`Sothe it es &thorn;at it es better to gyffe hy&mtail;-selfe &thorn;an
it es to gyffe of his, bot better es &thorn;e tane and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er &thorn;an es ane be it selfe, for lesse es a gud &thorn;an
twa.'  It es noghte swa: For whethire es better be callede Godde, or
His seruande.  Thow wate wele &thorn;at es better to be- callede
God&dtail;.  Bot &thorn;ase &thorn;at suffirs hunngere, thryste,
caulde and defaute, and o&thorn;er wrechidnes and mysese, calles oure
Lorde
<PB N="31">


Ihesu Criste Hym-selfe ; For He saise &thorn;us in &thorn;e Gosepelle,
`What als &thorn;ou dyde to &thorn;e leste of my&ntail;, &thorn;ou did
to me.'  Saynt Barnarde says, 'Thire pure hase noghte in erthe, ne
thire riche hase noghte in heue&ntail;; and &thorn;are-fore, if
&thorn;e Riche wi&llbar; it hafe, thaym byhoues bye it at &thorn;e
pure.'  Now wate I wele &thorn;ou couaytes to wyte whilke are verray
pure, and whilke noghte.  Now herke&ntail; with deuocyo&ntail;.
Su&mtail; are &thorn;at hase reches and lufes thaym, and &thorn;ase
are &thorn;e haldande and &thorn;e couaytourse of &thorn;is worlde.
Othere are &thorn;at hase &thorn;a&mtail; noghte, bot thay luffe
thay&mtail;, and thay walde hafe thay&mtail; gladly; and &thorn;ase
are &thorn;e wrechide beggers of &thorn;e worlde, and &thorn;e false
folke in religyo&ntail;, and &thorn;ase are als riche and richere
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;e o&thorn;er.  And of tha&mtail; Ihesu saise in
&thorn;e gospe&llbar;e &thorn;at `lyghtere it ware a camelle to passe
thurg&hbar;e a nedi&llbar; eghe, &thorn;an &thorn;e riche to co&mtail;
in-to &thorn;e blysse of heue&ntail;.'  Su&mtail; are &thorn;at hase
reches, bot thay lufe thaym noghte; Noghte for-thy &thorn;ay wi&llbar;
wele hafe &thorn;a&mtail;; and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e gud me&ntail;
of &thorn;e worlde &thorn;at dispendis wele that at &thorn;ay hafe.
Bot fone are of &thorn;ase.  &YOGH;it it are o&thorn;er &thorn;at hase
noghte reches, ne lufes noghte thaym, ne wi&llbar; noght hafe
&thorn;a&mtail;; and &thorn;ase are &thorn;e gude folke &thorn;at are
in religio&ntail; and &thorn;ase are sothefastly pure; and &thorn;airs
es &thorn;e Ioye of heue&ntail;, For &thorn;at es the benyso&ntail; of
&thorn;e pure.  Than it behufes &thorn;at &thorn;e riche hafe &thorn;e
reuere of &thorn;at benyso&ntail;; and &thorn;arefore may I say,
`Blyssede be &thorn;e pouer, for &thorn;aires es &thorn;e
kyngdo&mtail; and &thorn;e Ioye of heue&ntail;.'  And swa may I say of
&thorn;e riche, For &thorn;airs es pyne of helle.  Alswa pouer
&thorn;ay are &thorn;at hase pouerte and lufes na reches; and pouer
&thorn;ay are &thorn;at hase reches and lufes pouert.</P>

<P>&para; Now aftire &thorn;is, awe &thorn;e to wyte whylke are
&thorn;e seue&ntail; prayers of &thorn;e Pater noster, &thorn;at duse
away a&llbar; i&llbar; and purchase a&llbar; gude.  And &thorn;ase
seue&ntail; prayers er contende in &thorn;e Pater noster, &thorn;e
whilke oure Lorde Ihesu Criste kennde ti&llbar; His discyples, how
&thorn;ay [suld] pray Godd &thorn;e Fadire, and said thaym one
&thorn;is manere, `Whe&ntail; &yogh;e<MILESTONE N="203" UNIT="leaf"> sa&llbar; praye, one &thorn;is
wyese sa&llbar; &yogh;e say, Pater noster qui es in celis, &amp;c.'
Now, my frende, wit &thorn;ou &thorn;at oure Lorde Ihesu Cryste kennes
vs in &thorn;e gospe&llbar;e to make &thorn;is prayere.  And
&thorn;are-fore I walde at &thorn;ou wyste at &thorn;e begynnynge
whate es prayere or orysone, and sythy&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ou
vndirstande
 
<!-- 0017.p32-33.txt -->
<PB N="32">


&thorn;e prayere of &thorn;e pater noster.  Prayere or Oryso&ntail; es
noghte elles bot &yogh;ernyng of saule, with certayne trayste
&thorn;at it commes &thorn;at &thorn;ou prayes.  And in &thorn;at
trayste vs settis Ihesu Criste whe&ntail; He kennes vs to call Godde
oure fadyre &thorn;at es in heue&ntail;, For in Hym sa&llbar; man hafe
certayne trayste &thorn;at He may and wi&llbar; a&llbar; gudnes gyffe
&thorn;at oure saule ka&ntail; &yogh;erne, and meki&llbar; mare;
&thorn;e whilke es betakynde by &thorn;ise wordes, Qui es in celis,
&thorn;at es to say, &thorn;e whilke es in heue&ntail;.  For if Godde
wi&llbar; ca&llbar; Hym-selfe oure fadyre, &thorn;an He makes vs to
wiet &thorn;at He lufes vs als childyre, and at He wi&llbar; gyfe us
a&llbar; &thorn;at we hafe myster of.  Bot certanly if a&llbar;
&thorn;e lufe &thorn;at euer had fadire or modire vn-to &thorn;aire
childyre, or a&llbar; othire lufes of &thorn;is worlde ware gedirde
to-gedyre in a lufe, and &yogh;it &thorn;at lufe ware multipliede als
meki&llbar; als mans herte moghte thynke, &yogh;it it moghte na thynge
atteyne to &thorn;e lufe &thorn;at Godde oure fadyre hase vn-ti&llbar;
vs, &thorn;are whare we are hys enmys.  And &thorn;at sa&llbar; we
wele see thurg&hbar; &thorn;e grace of Godde, If we se one what manere
He is oure Fadyr, and what He has do&ntail; for vs.  Wit &thorn;ou,
&thorn;at whe&ntail; God made a&llbar; creaturs of noghte, we rede
noghte &thorn;at He made any creature ti&llbar; His lyknes bot
ma&ntail; allanne; and &thorn;are-fore Godd He es, and makere of
a&llbar; thynges of &thorn;e worlde, Bot He es noghte &thorn;aire
fadyre; Bot vn-ti&llbar; vs, thurghe His awe&ntail; myghte fu&llbar;
of mercy, es He Godd and makere and Fadyr, For &thorn;at our saule es
lelly lyke vn-ti&llbar; &thorn;e lyknes of &thorn;e Fadyr, and
&thorn;e So&ntail;, and &thorn;e Haly Gaste, &thorn;at ere hallyly a
God&dtail; and persons thre.  And a&llbar; &thorn;is werlde He hase
made to serue man, whils mane wi&llbar; duelle in His lele lufe als
His awe&ntail; childyre.  Bot als tyte als we twy&ntail; fra &thorn;at
lele lufe, for lufe of &thorn;is lyfe, or for any o&thorn;er thynge,
we losse &thorn;e lordechipe of &thorn;is worlde, and becommes
thralles dreryly to &thorn;e deue&llbar;e, &thorn;are we ware be-fore
fre, and ayers of &thorn;e erytage of &thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of
heue&ntail;, and to welde &thorn;e welthe of &thorn;is werlde.  Allas
may saye, Allas! Allas! what here es a sorowfu&llbar; chaunge whasa it
vndyrstode ! Wit &thorn;ou wele &thorn;at here es gret lykynge of
lufe, when Godd &thorn;at es with-owtty&ntail; begynnynge, and es
withowtte&ntail; chaungeyng, and duellys with-owtty&ntail; Endynge,
for He es al-&thorn;ir-myghtyeste and al&thorn;irwyseste, and alswa
al&thorn;ire-beste
<PB N="33">



&thorn;at mannes herte may noghte thynke, in whaym es lufe and Ioy
endles, here, I say, es taky&ntail; of gret lufe, &thorn;at He deyned
Hym to make vs ti&llbar; His awe&ntail; lyknes righte als we had bene
His awen chose&ntail; childyre, and moghte hafe lefte vs to be a
litti&llbar; vyle matire als we ware made of oure modyr, &thorn;at
vile es to neue&ntail; ; or He moghte hafe made vs at His wi&llbar;
anyky&ntail; o&thorn;er bestis; and &thorn;a&ntail; had we dyede
to-gedire, bathe body and saule.  Bot when He hade made vs man, and
gafe<MILESTONE N="203 bk." UNIT="leaf"> vs &thorn;e saule to His awe&ntail; lyknes, (louede and luffede
be &thorn;at Lorde !) for to be ayers of &thorn;e Erytage of
heue&ntail; and lyfe in &thorn;at gret Ioye with-owtte&ntail; Ende,
Now es na herte sa herde &thorn;at it na moghte nesche, and lufe
Swylke a God&dtail; with all his myghte.  And his herte suld melte,
filled of Ioy, if it thoghte sothely of &thorn;at grace &thorn;at oure
Lorde hase do&ntail; ti&llbar; vs by-fore a&llbar; o&thorn;er
creaturs. And &yogh;itt did He mare thurg&hbar;e His meki&llbar;
mercy; For, whene we ware, thurg&hbar;e oure Sorowfu&llbar; sy&ntail;,
twynnede fra God&dtail;, oure Sweteste Fadire, and become thralles to
&thorn;e i&llbar; gaste, Than He, thurg&hbar;e His maste mercy, Sente
His awe&ntail; Sonne, &thorn;at with Hym es God&dtail; in His Godede,
for to take flesche and blode of &thorn;e Virgy&ntail; Marie,
Mayde&ntail; and modyr, lastand in Ioy; and one &thorn;is manere did
He &thorn;e dede.  In state of thra&llbar;e tuke He oure flesc&hbar;e
to suffre &thorn;e gylteste pouerte, and schame, and noyes, and
paynnes, &thorn;at neuer dyd i&llbar; ne na maner of sy&ntail;, and
Sythe&ntail; delyuerde Hym ti&llbar; &thorn;e vileste dede, and
&thorn;e schamefulleste &thorn;at man moghte thynke, to delyuer vs
wreches of sorowfu&llbar; bandis, and of &thorn;e pynand preso&ntail;
puttid in he&llbar;, and to make vs to comme ti&llbar; &thorn;e heghe
heue&ntail;, whare we sa&llbar; be als kynges corounde in blyse, if we
do &thorn;e wi&llbar; of &thorn;at swet Lorde, &thorn;at for vs
ordeynede Hym to dye one &thorn;e crosse als &thorn;ofe He had benne a
wykkid thefe.  Dere Frende, nowe hase &thorn;ou here twa thyngez in
&thorn;e whilke Godde hase schewede vs &thorn;at He es oure fadire,
and &thorn;at He lufes vs als His awe&ntail; childyre &thorn;are we
are agayne Hy&mtail; with oure wykked sy&ntail;.  The firste es,
&thorn;at He made vs ti&llbar; His awe&ntail; lyknes; and &thorn;e
to&thorn;er es, &thorn;at He boghte vs fra presou&ntail; with His
precyouse dede of His manhede.  For &thorn;e fyrste, es man
halde&ntail; ti&llbar; Hym, for to lufe Hym with a&llbar; his
herte. Bot &thorn;an may &thorn;ou aske, `what sa&llbar; I do Hym for
&thorn;e to&thorn;er


 
<!-- 0018.p34-35.txt -->
<PB N="34">


thynge?  For if I sa&llbar; wit&hbar; pouerhede lofe God&dtail;
&thorn;e Fadyr, and lufe Hym and serue Him with a&llbar; my saule and
with a&llbar; my herte in a&llbar; thynges, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at He
made me of noghte and gafe me saule aftir His awe&ntail; lyknes,
&mdash; als it was commandyd in &thorn;e alde lawe be-fore Godde was
borne and be-com man for vs, &mdash; what moghte I now do Hym,
whe&ntail; He, for me wrechid synnere, sa meki&llbar; Hym lawede
&thorn;at He walde becomme ma&ntail;, and He gafe Hym to me,
whe&ntail; He, thurghe His sweteste mercy, walde dye for me, and of
&thorn;e maste noyouse and &thorn;e moste vile dede &thorn;at euer was
thoghte ? I wate neuer what I may say here; For if I myghte lyffe a
hundrethe &yogh;ere, and if I moghte in &thorn;at tym, ilk a day at a
ty&mtail;, dye als vile ded als He for me dide, &yogh;it ne ware it
noghte ynence His gret gyftez, when He es sothely said Goddes Sonne of
heue&ntail;, and gaffe Hym selfe ti&llbar; vs, &thorn;at tynte was for
sy&ntail; thurg&hbar;, and put in to &thorn;e pyne of helle, and
&thorn;are, in &thorn;e dispytte of Hym, seruede to &thorn;e deuelle.
How sulde we &thorn;a&ntail; &yogh;elde Hym &thorn;e gude gret gyfte,
whe&ntail; He walde sende His awe&ntail; Sone to be pynede for oure
sy&ntail; ?`</P>

<P>Now I sa&llbar; lere the, if God gyffe me grace, how oure dere
Fadir askes nane o&thorn;er store bot that we, with herte, knawe oure
awe&ntail; Febillnes and oure wrechidnes, &thorn;at we hafe for oure
awe&ntail; sy&ntail;.  <MILESTONE N="204" UNIT="leaf">Thane sa&llbar; we be in bitternes of penance,
and crye ti&llbar; Hym faste mercy, &thorn;at He vs saue for His haly
name, For of oure selfe hafe we noghte Hym for to &yogh;elde ;
&thorn;are-fore said the prophete in &thorn;e psalme, Quid retribuam
Domino pro omnibus que <CORR SIC="retrebuit" RESP="Perry">retribuit</CORR> michi ?  Calicem salutaris accipiam,
et nomen Domini invocabo, etc'. &thorn;at es, 'what sa&llbar; I
&yogh;elde to God for a&llbar; His gud gyftes &thorn;at He me gyffes
als Lorde,with-owtte&ntail; my deserte? The coppe of hele I sa&llbar;
take, and ca&llbar;e &thorn;e name of my lorde.'  The cope of hele
whare-of dranke oure Lord Ihesu oure Saueour, &thorn;at es, the
bytternes of &thorn;e penance in His grete pynes, and &thorn;at man in
a&llbar; his thoghtez calles Godez name, &thorn;at sothefastly knawes
&thorn;at he hase noghte of hym-selfe bot sorowe and synne.  And wit
thou &thorn;at, if sothefastenes be sett faste in thi saule, &thorn;e
mare &thorn;at &thorn;ou knawes &thorn;e for wrechide and feby&llbar;,
&thorn;e mare sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
<PB N="35">



meke &thorn;e, and ca&llbar;e on Hys mercy.  And &thorn;us it was of
oure swete Lady, mayde&ntail; and modyr; For scho had mare of grace
&thorn;ane any in this lyfe, man or woma&ntail; &thorn;at euer was
borne, Thare-fore scho halde hir lesse and lawere &thorn;an any
o&thorn;er wyghte, and mare cryede scho mercy &thorn;an any o&thorn;er
man, whe&ntail; sothefaste Goddes So&ntail; lighte in hir wambe.  My
dere frende, se now aftir-warde why oure Lord Ihesu kennes vs in
&thorn;e Gospelle to saye `oure Fadire,' and noghte `my Fadir'; For by
&thorn;at wi&llbar; He ken&ntail; vs &thorn;at we suld gedyre a&llbar;
men with vs in oure prayers, For a&llbar; ere oure brethire, crystende
and vncristen&dtail; me&ntail;, For &thorn;at a&llbar; of a
gouernaylle hafe we a Fadyr.  And &thorn;at &thorn;ou may &thorn;is
thynge, thurghe &thorn;e grace of Godd, clerelyere See, Gyffe gude
Entente ti&llbar; &thorn;at at I say.  Hym calles &thorn;ou `thi
fleschely bro&thorn;er,' &thorn;at hase his body of &thorn;e same
ma&ntail; and woma&ntail; of whaym &thorn;ou hase thyne.  Thane
sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wele halde hym &thorn;i bro&thorn;er &thorn;at
hase his saule of &thorn;e Same fadir of heue&ntail; of whaym
&thorn;ou hase &thorn;i saule, and of swylke a kynd, and of swylke a
lyknes; For als wele made Godd ilke ma&ntail; ti&llbar; lyknes of
&thorn;e Trinyte als He did &thorn;e.  And &thorn;is bro&thorn;erhede
mare suld we lufe, and mare dere halde, &thorn;an &thorn;e
bro&thorn;erhede of &thorn;e flesche, in als meki&llbar; als &thorn;e
saule es mare noby&llbar; &thorn;an &thorn;i flesche, and in als
meki&llbar; als God&dtail;, oure fadir, of heue&ntail;, es mare
nobi&llbar;, and mare for to lufe, &thorn;an oure fleschly fadir. And
&thorn;at suld we do if we saghe als clerely wit&hbar; oure gastely
eghe als we do with oure bodyly eghe.  Bot for-thy &thorn;at we see
noghte bot with &thorn;e fleschely eghe, als it ware bestes, we hafe
na knawynge ne na lufe bot of &thorn;at bro&thorn;erhede &thorn;at
commes of &thorn;e flesche stynkande and foule.  Allas! Allas! what
sorowfu&llbar; thynge thus hase blyndid vs!  Certis, na thynge mare
blyndis manes saule &thorn;ane lufe of erthely thynge &thorn;at sonne
takes ende.  For-&thorn;i behufes ma&ntail; lefe his propire
wi&llbar;, if he wi&llbar; perfitly knawe &thorn;e lufe-somest
bro&thorn;erhede.  Whare-of now meki&llbar; I hafe spoke&ntail;, For
whate-sa-euer we hafe in body or in saule of gudnes or of <MILESTONE
N="204 bk." UNIT="leaf">fayrenes, we
hafe it of oure fadyr of heue&ntail;, God&dtail;, &thorn;at es
ti&llbar; vs fadir, and Euenly ti&llbar; a&llbar; His creaturs, noghte
anely for His makynge of noghte, ne for His gouernyng of His grace,
for His purchasyage &thorn;at He made of vs &thorn;at ware tynt


 
<!-- 0019.p36-37.txt -->
<PB N="36">


childir, with His flesche and His blode &thorn;at He for vs gafe, als
Saynt Austy&ntail; &thorn;e nobi&llbar; clerke witnes.  He sayse
`&thorn;e Fadir gaffe His So&ntail;, thurg&hbar; whaym He walde by vs
thralles; He gafe &thorn;e Haly Gaste, thurg&hbar; whay&mtail; He
walde purchase &thorn;e thralles in His childire.  &THORN;e Sonn, He
gafe in pryse of raunso&ntail;; &thorn;e Haly Gaste, in preuelege of
purchase; and &thorn;ar-fore &thorn;e Fadir kepis Hym selfe in Erytage
ti&llbar; His childir &thorn;at He purchase[d].'  And &thorn;arefore,
dere frende, na ma&ntail; sa&llbar; mystrayste of &thorn;e lufe of His
swete Fadirhede, and of His dere pete; For mare es His mercy
&thorn;a&ntail; a&llbar; oure wykkednes; For wha sa calles ti&llbar;
Hym with a&llbar; his herte, with-owtte&ntail; faile He wi&llbar; here
hy&mtail;, for He es fu&llbar; of mercy. And &thorn;are-fore, als I
be-fore saide, with &yogh;ernynge of saule and certayne trayste, calle
apo&ntail; Hym trewely with a&llbar; thi herte.  He es &thorn;i Fadir
pereles, &thorn;at purchacecez &thorn;e pees; and saye traystely
ti&llbar; Hy&mtail; als Hym-selfe vs lerede, Pater noster qui es in
celis, &thorn;at es to say, Oure Fadir that es in heue&ntail;;
sanctificetur nomen tuum, &thorn;at es to say, halyed be &thorn;i
name; adveniat regnum tuum, it co&mtail;, &thorn;i kyngedo&mtail;;
Fiat voluntas tua, sicut in celo et in terr&acirc;, &thorn;i wi&llbar;
be donne, swa in erthe als it es in heue&ntail;; panem nostrum
cotidianum da nobis hodie, Oure ylke day brede &thorn;ou gyffe vs to
day; Et dimitte nobis debita nostra, sicut et nos dimittimus
debitoribus nostris, and forgyffe vs oure dettis als we forgyffe our
dettours ; Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem, and suffire vs noghte be
ledde in-to fandyngis, Set libera nos a malo, bot delyuer vs fra
a&llbar; i&llbar; thynges Amen !  &THORN;at es to say, Swa mot it be!
Now, my dere frende, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wyt &thorn;at &thorn;is
Oryso&ntail; passes a&llbar; o&thorn;er prayers, pryncypally in twa
thynges, &thorn;at es to say, in worthynes and in profyte.  In
worthynes, for &thorn;at God Hym-selfe mad it; and for-&thorn;i do
&thorn;ay gret schame and gret vnreuerence ti&llbar; Ihesu, Goddes
So&ntail;, &thorn;at takes &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar; wordis rynnand
and curius, and leues &thorn;e prayere &thorn;at He vs kennede,
&thorn;at wate a&llbar; &thorn;e wi&llbar; of God&dtail; &thorn;e
Fadir, and &thorn;e whilke orysone commes mare ti&llbar; His plesynge,
and whate thynges &thorn;e wrechede caytyfe hase myster at pray fore.
Alswa, als I hafe sayde, He wate anely a&llbar; &thorn;e Fadir
wy&llbar;, and He wate a&llbar; oure nede; and &thorn;are-fore a
hundrethe thousande er
<PB N="37">
dyssayued with multyplicatione of wordes and of orysouns; For, when
&thorn;ay wene &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe grete deuocyo&ntail;,
&thorn;a&ntail; hafe &thorn;ai a fulle fleschely lykynge, For-thy
&thorn;at ilk a fleschely lykynge delytes &thorn;a&mtail; kyndely in
swylke turnede langage ; and &thorn;are-fore I walde &thorn;at
&thorn;ou war warre, For I say &thorn;e sykerly, &thorn;at it es a
foule lychery for to delyte &thorn;e in rymmes and slyke gulyardy;
&yogh;it one a-no&thorn;er syde, Saynt Austyne, and Saynt Gregore, and
o&thorn;er halowes &thorn;at prayede als was &thorn;aire lykynge.  I
blame noghte prayers, bot I blame &thorn;ase &thorn;at lefes &thorn;e
prayere of God&dtail; &thorn;at Hym-selfe made, and lerede vs for to
pray, &thorn;at es, Pater noster, and takes &thorn;a&mtail; ti&llbar;
&thorn;e Orysons of a synfu&llbar; Saynte whare &thorn;ay fynde it
wrette&ntail;, For oure Lorde Ihesus Hym-selfe sayse in the
<MILESTONE N="205" UNIT="leaf">gospe&llbar;, `when &yogh;e wi&llbar; praye, prayes noghte with many
wordes, bot praye one &thorn;is manere, Pater noster &amp;c'.'</P>

<P>&para; Dere frende, &yogh;it sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wit one
ano&thorn;er syde &thorn;at &thorn;e Pater noster passes a&llbar;
o&thorn;er prayers in worthynes; For &thorn;are-in es contende
a&llbar; thyngez what-sa we hafe myster of, ti&llbar; &thorn;is lyfe
or ti&llbar; &thorn;e to&thorn;er.  For we praye &thorn;are-in
God&dtail; &thorn;e Fadyr, &thorn;at He delyuer vs of a&llbar; illes,
and &thorn;at He gyffe vs a&llbar; gudes, and &thorn;at He make vs
swylke &thorn;at we may neuer do i&llbar;, ne &thorn;at we may noghte
fayle of gude.  And now, a&llbar; &thorn;e i&llbar;e &thorn;at vs
greues, ou&thorn;er es it, ille &thorn;at es donne, or it es i&llbar;e
for to co&mtail;, or elles it es ille &thorn;at we suffire nowe.  Of
&thorn;at ille &thorn;at es donne and passede, we praye oure swete
Lorde &thorn;at He delyuer vs &thorn;er-of, whe&ntail; we say Dimitte
nobis debita nostra, etc'.  We pray Hym delyuer vs of i&llbar;
&thorn;at es for to co&mtail;, whe&ntail; we say et ne nos inducas in
temptacionem.  Of illes &thorn;at we suffire nowe, we praye Hy&mtail;
&thorn;at He delyuer vs, whe&ntail; we say Set libera nos a malo.
&para; &YOGH;it, dere Frende, on a o&thorn;er syde, wit &thorn;ou
&thorn;at a&llbar; maner of gude &thorn;at es, Ou&thorn;er it es
erthely gude, or gastely gude, or gude lastande endles.  For erthely
gude we praye, whe&ntail; we saye Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis
hodie; For gastely gude we praye, whe&ntail; we say Fiat voluntas tua,
sicut in celo et in terra; For endles gude we praye, when we say
Adveniat regnum tuum; and confermyng of a&llbar; this we praye,
whe&ntail; we say Sanctificetur nomen tuum.


 
<!-- 0020.p38-39.txt -->
<PB N="38"></P>



<P>&para; Now, my dere frende, &thorn;ese ere seue&ntail; prayers of
&thorn;e Ewangelle &thorn;at oure Lorde Ihesu Criste kenne&dtail;
ti&llbar; His dyscypi&llbar;s.  And &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wit &thorn;at
&thorn;ese foure wordes &thorn;at comes be-fore, &thorn;at es to wit,
Pater noster qui es in celis, leres vs how we sa&llbar; praye, and
what oure selfe sa&llbar; be in prayere; For we sa&llbar;, in ylke ane
Oryso&ntail;, haue foure thynges, &thorn;at es to say, perfite lufe
ti&llbar; Hym ti&llbar; whaym we praye, and certayne trayste to haue
&thorn;at at we praye fore, and stabi&llbar; trout&hbar; in Hym in
whaym we trowe, and sothefaste mekenes of &thorn;at, that of oure
selfe, na gude we haue.  Perfite lufe es vndirstande&ntail; in
&thorn;is worde Pater, For ylke a creature kyndly lufes his Fadir.
Certayne trayst es contende in &thorn;is worde noster; For if He be
ours, &thorn;an may we sekerly trayst in Hym &thorn;at He es
halde&ntail; ti&llbar; vs.  Stabi&llbar; trouthe es take&ntail; in
&thorn;ise wordes Qui es ; For whe&ntail; we say qui es, &thorn;an
graunt we wele &thorn;at God&dtail; es &thorn;at we neuer sawe; and
&thorn;at es ryghte trout&hbar;e, For trouthe es na no&thorn;er thyng
bot trowyng of thyng &thorn;at may noghte be sene.  Sothefaste mekenes
es betakynde in &thorn;is worde In celis, For when we thynke how He es
heghe in Ioy, and how we are here lawe in besynes, tha&ntail; we are
mekide. Bot whe&ntail; we hafe festenede &thorn;ere foure thynges in
oure hertes, &thorn;an may we hardyly praye, and saye with a&llbar;
oure affeccyo&ntail;, Sanctificetur nomen tuum, &thorn;at es to say,
`haly be thi name!' als swa stabi&llbar; &thorn;i name, &thorn;at es,
Fadir, in vs, &thorn;at we be one &thorn;at manere &thorn;i childire
&thorn;at we do na thyng &thorn;at be agaynes &thorn;i wi&llbar;, and
that euer-mare we doo &thorn;at at commes to &thorn;i plesyng,
thurg&hbar; grauntynge of &thorn;i grace.  And for-thi &thorn;at we
may noghte euer-mare do &thorn;at perfitely whyls we ere in &thorn;is
caytifede worlde, &thorn;are-fore pray we &thorn;us, and sayse,
Adveniat regnum tuum, &thorn;at es to say, it co&mtail; ti&llbar; vs,
&thorn;i kyngdo&mtail;, &thorn;at we regne in &thorn;e, Ihesu, in
&thorn;is lyfe thurg&hbar; thi grace, and &thorn;ou in vs in &thorn;e
to&thorn;er lyfe thurg&hbar; Ioy.  And &thorn;is ilke we praye for
&thorn;ase &thorn;at are in purgatorie; and for-&thorn;i &thorn;at we
neuer-mare may hafe <MILESTONE N="205 bk." UNIT="leaf">parte with Ioye of heue&ntail; if we do noghte thi
wi&llbar; in erthe, &thorn;are-fore we praye thus, Fiat voluntas tua,
sicut in celo et in terra, &thorn;at es to say, thi wi&llbar; be
do&ntail;e, als in heue&ntail;, swa in erthe.  Alswa say `make vs to
do &thorn;i wy&llbar;,' &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;ou gyffe
<PB N="39">



vs grace to do a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou commandes, and to lefe
a&llbar; &thorn;at &thorn;ou defendis, and &thorn;at swa in erthe als
in heue&ntail;, &thorn;at es to say, als Michaelle, and Gabrielle, and
Raphaelle, Cheruby&ntail; and Seraphy&ntail;, and a&llbar; &thorn;e
o&thorn;er ange&llbar;s and archange&llbar;s, and a&llbar; &thorn;ase
&thorn;at are Ordeynede to &thorn;e endles lyfe in Ioy, in ilke a
kynde, in ilke ane ordire, and in ilke ane elde, thi wille duse; and
for-thi &thorn;at we may noghte do &thorn;i wi&llbar; whi&llbar;s we
lyffe in &thorn;is body, if &thorn;ou ne sustayne vs noghte,
&thorn;are-fore say we &thorn;us, Panem nostrum cotidianum da nobis
hodie, &thorn;at es to say, Oure ilke day brede &thorn;ou gyffe vs
to-day; als swa say `&thorn;ou gyffe vs Force in body and in saule,
and hele, if it be &thorn;i wi&llbar;, of &thorn;e tane and offe
&thorn;e to&thorn;er.'  And here es for to wit, &thorn;at &thorn;are
es thre maners of brede, &thorn;at es, bodyly brede, &thorn;at es to
say, Fode and clethynge; &thorn;are es brede gastely, &thorn;at es to
say, of haly wrytte &thorn;e leryng; and &thorn;are es &thorn;e brede
of Eukaryste, &thorn;at es &thorn;e grace in &thorn;e sacrament of
&thorn;e autere, for to comfort&hbar;e &thorn;e kynde of &thorn;e tane
and &thorn;e to&thorn;er.</P>

<P>Bot for-thi &thorn;at we ere worthi na gudnes whills we ere
bownde&ntail; in syn&ntail;, &thorn;are-fore say we &thorn;us, Dimitte
nobis debita nostra, sicut et nos dimittimus debitoribus nostris,
&thorn;is es to say, `Forgyffe vs oure dettis als we forgyffe oure
dettours.' &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wyt &thorn;are oure synns byndis oure
dettours to pynne; &thorn;are-fore we pray Ihesu to for-gyff vs
synnes, &thorn;at es to say, a&llbar; &thorn;at we hafe synnede in
thoghte, in worde and in dede; and &thorn;at ryghte als we for-gyffe
ti&llbar; &thorn;ase &thorn;at hase mysdone agaynes vs.  And
for-&thorn;i &thorn;at a lytti&llbar; vs helpes to hafe forgyfnes of
sy&ntail;, if we may noghte kepe vs fra sy&ntail;, &thorn;are-fore
pray we &thorn;us, Et ne nos inducas in temptacionem, and &thorn;is es
to say, `lede us no&yogh;te in-to na fandyngis, als swa say, Suffere
vs noghte be ouer-comme&ntail; in fandyngez of &thorn;e deue&llbar;,
ne of &thorn;e flesc&hbar;, ne of &thorn;e werlde.  And noghte allanly
we pray &thorn;at we be delyuered of a&llbar; euy&llbar; fandyngez,
Bot alswa we pray &thorn;at we be delyuered of a&llbar; i&llbar;
thyngis, whe&ntail; we say, Set libera nos a malo; and &thorn;is es to
say, `Bot delyuer vs of a&llbar; i&llbar; thyngis,' &thorn;at es, of
body and of saule, of sy&ntail; and of pyne, For sy&ntail; that now es
or sa&llbar; be.  Say we Amen ! &thorn;at es to say, `swa be it!' and
for-thi sayse oure Lorde


 
<!-- 0021.p40-41.txt -->
<PB N="40">


Ihesu Criste in &thorn;e gospelle, `What sa &thorn;ou prayes my fadir
in my name, He sa&llbar; do it;' and &thorn;er-fore say at &thorn;e
Ende, Per Dominum nostrum Iesum Cristum, filium tuum, &amp;c'.</P>

<P>And now, my dere frende, vndirstande noghte &thorn;at &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; say &thorn;i Pater noster with mouthe, als I hafe it here
wrety&ntail; be-fore &thorn;e.  Bot say a&llbar; anely &thorn;e nakede
lettir with &thorn;i mouthe, and thynke in &thorn;i herte of this
&thorn;at I hafe said here, of ilke a worde by it-selfe; and rekk
noghte &thorn;of &thorn;ou ne multyply many Pater nosters; For it es
better to say a Pater noster with gude deuocyo&ntail;, &thorn;a&ntail;
a thousande with-owtte&ntail; deuocyo&ntail;; For &thorn;us sais
Saynte Paule appertly; he sayse, `me ware leuer say fyve wordes in
herte deuotely, &thorn;ane fyve thousande <MILESTONE N="206" UNIT="leaf">with my mouthe
with-owtte&ntail; lykynge.'  And one &thorn;e same manere sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou say and do at thyne offece in &thorn;e qweire ; for swa
sayse &thorn;e prophete, Psallite sapienter; and &thorn;at es to say,
Synges and versy wyesly,' &thorn;at es, to say or to syng wyesly,
&thorn;at es, &thorn;at thi herte be one &thorn;at at &thorn;ou saise,
and one &thorn;at at o&thorn;er saise, &thorn;at &thorn;ou here it
besyly; For if &thorn;i body be at thi seruyce, and &thorn;i mouthe
speke one a wyse, and thi herte thynke of wrechidnes caytefly,
&thorn;an es &thorn;ou twynne&dtail;; For when &thorn;ou swa es
twynne&dtail;, &thorn;ou tynes &thorn;e mede of &thorn;i seruyce; For
&thorn;e awe to serue God&dtail; with a&llbar; &thorn;i herte, with
a&llbar; &thorn;i saule, and with a&llbar; &thorn;i vertu; and swa
&thorn;ou may pay &thorn;i God&dtail;.  Bot &thorn;are es many thynges
&thorn;at ere cause of swylke wrechede twynnynge, als mete, drynke,
Reste, cleythynge, layke, discorde, Thoghte, laboure, hethynge.  These
makes hippynge, homerynge, of medles momellynge.  And &thorn;are-fore
take kepe what oure Lorde Ihesu Criste saise in &thorn;e
gospe&llbar;e: `Firste,' He saise, `sekes &thorn;e kyngdo&mtail; of
heue&ntail;, and a&llbar; &thorn;at &yogh;e hafe myster of sa&llbar;
be gyffe&ntail; &yogh;owe with-owtty&ntail; any askynge.'</P>

<P>Thare-fore, dere Frende, &thorn;ou sa&llbar; wit what &thorn;ou
sa&llbar; hafe in &thorn;e blysse of heue&ntail;. Wit &thorn;ou wele
&thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; hafe Seue&ntail; gyftes in body, and
Seue&ntail; in saule, &thorn;at es to say, Fairenes in body with-
owtty&ntail; fylth, lyghtenes with-owtty&ntail; slewt&hbar;, Force
with-owtte&ntail; Feblesce, Frenes with-owtte&ntail; thrall edome,
lykynge with-owtte&ntail; noye, lufelynes with-owtty&ntail; envye,
hele with-owtty&ntail; sekenes, lange lyfe with-owtty&ntail;
ende. Thou sa&llbar; hafe in saule, Wysedome
<PB N="41">



with-owtte&ntail; ygnorance, Frenchipe with-owtte&ntail;
hateredy&ntail;, Accorde with-owtte&ntail; discorde, Myghte
with-owtte&ntail; wayknes, honour with-owtte&ntail; dishonour,
Sekirnes with-owtte&ntail; drede, Ioy with-owtte&ntail; sorowe.  Bot
&thorn;e wreches in helle, a&llbar; &thorn;e reuerce, bot&hbar; in
body and in saule, &thorn;at es to say, Fylt&hbar; with-owtty&ntail;
fairenes, Slouthe with-owtte&ntail; lyghtenes, Feblesce
with-owtte&ntail; force, Thraldo&mtail; with-owtte&ntail; freenes,
Angwyse with-owtte&ntail; lykynge, Sekenes with-owtte&ntail; hele, ded
with-owtte&ntail; ende.  Thare sa&llbar; be in &thorn;air saules,
Ignorance with-owtty&ntail; Wysdome, hatredy&ntail; with-owtt e&ntail;
lufe, Discorde with-owtte&ntail; Accorde, feblesce with-owtte&ntail;
powere, Schame with-owtte&ntail; honour, Drede with-owtte&ntail;
sekernes, and Sorowe with-owtte&ntail; Ioy.  And for &thorn;is
sa&llbar; &thorn;ou seke with a&llbar; &thorn;i myghte, &thorn;at
&thorn;ou may wy&ntail; &thorn;e Ioye of heue&ntail;; For &thorn;are
es sa gret Ioye and sa meki&llbar; swettnes &thorn;at, if &thorn;ou
myghte lyffe fra &thorn;e begynnynge of &thorn;e worlde vn-ti&llbar;
&thorn;e ende, and hafe a&llbar; &thorn;e lykynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou
couthe ordeyne, &yogh;it &thorn;ou sulde with gret ryghte lefe
a&llbar; &thorn;ase for to be a day in &thorn;e Ioy of heue&ntail;.
And thus endys &thorn;e to&thorn;er degre of contemplacyone, &thorn;at
es to say, &thorn;e contemplacione of haly writte; of &thorn;e whylke,
if &thorn;ou take gud kepe in &thorn;i herte, it sa&llbar; be lyghte
vnto &thorn;e, ilke a worde to halde.  One ane o&thorn;er syde, if
&thorn;ou hafe mater to speke vn-to &thorn;e clerkez, be &thorn;ay
neuer sa wyse, or to lewede men, be &thorn;ay neuer so ruyde, of
&thorn;e clerkes &thorn;ou mofe som matirs of &thorn;is, and alswa at
&thorn;ou may lere more.  And whe&ntail; &thorn;ou spekes ti&llbar;
sympi&llbar; me&ntail;, and ruyde, <MILESTONE N="206 bk." UNIT="leaf">gladly &thorn;ou lere
&thorn;a&mtail; with swettnes, For &thorn;ou hafe enoghe whare-of
&thorn;ou may speke, and how &thorn;ou sa&llbar; &thorn;i lyfe amende
and gouerne, and o&thorn;er menes alswa.</P>

<P>&THORN;e thirde degre of contemplacyo&ntail; es in God&dtail;
Hym-selfe.  And &thorn;at may be on twa maners, &thorn;at es,
with-owtte&ntail; in His manhede, and in His Godhede so blyschede.
For &thorn;us saise Saynt Austy&ntail;, For-&thorn;i be-come
God&dtail; ma&ntail;, For to make mane to Se God&dtail; in his kynde;
For whe&thorn;er so&mtail; he &yogh;ode with-in or with-owtte&ntail;,
euer-mare moghte man fynde pasture ; with-owtte&ntail;, thurg&hbar;
consederacyo&ntail; of His manhe&dtail;; with-in, thurghe
contemplacyo&ntail; of His Godhede. Of His manhede sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
thynke


 
<!-- 0022.p42-43.txt -->
<PB N="42">


thre thyngez: &thorn;e meknes of His Incarnacyo&ntail;, &thorn;e
swetenes of His conuersasio&ntail;, and &thorn;e grete charite of His
passione. Bot &thorn;is may &thorn;ou noghte do a&llbar; att anes; and
&thorn;are-fore hafe I twynned the thaym by &thorn;e Seue&ntail;
houres of &thorn;e daye &thorn;at &thorn;ou saise in &thorn;e kyrke,
Swa &thorn;at na&ntail; houre passe the, &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne
sa&llbar; be swetely ocupye&dtail; in &thorn;i herte.  Bot nowe for to
do &thorn;is, &thorn;an sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wit &thorn;at ti&llbar;
ilke ane houre of &thorn;e daye es dowby&llbar; medytacyo&ntail;, ane
of His passyo&ntail;, and ano&thorn;er of &thorn;e to&thorn;er
seso&ntail;.  &para; Now, dere frende, before matyns sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e swete byrt&hbar;e of Ihesu Cryste
al-&thorn;er-fyrste, and sythy&ntail; eftyrwarde of His passio&ntail;.
Of His byrt&hbar;, sa&llbar; thou thynke besyly &thorn;e ty&mtail;,
and &thorn;e stede and &thorn;e houre, &thorn;at oure Lorde Ihesu
Criste was borne of His modir Marie.  &THORN;e tyme was in
myd-wyntter, whe&ntail; it was maste calde; &thorn;e houre was at
mydnyghte, &thorn;e hardeste houre &thorn;at es; &thorn;e stede was in
mydwarde &thorn;e strete, in a house with-owtte&ntail; walles.  In
clowtis was He wonde&ntail;, and als a chylde was He bunde&ntail;; and
in a crybbe by-fore ane oxe and ane asse, &thorn;at lufely lorde layde
was, for &thorn;are was na no&thorn;er stede voyde.  And here
sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e kepynge of Marye, and of hir
childe, and of hir spouse Iosep&hbar; &mdash; wat Ioye Ihesu &thorn;am
sente.  Thou sa&llbar; thynke also of &thorn;e hyrdes &thorn;at saw
&thorn;e taky&ntail; of His byrt&hbar;e; and &thorn;ou sa&llbar;
thynke of &thorn;e swete felachippe of Ange&llbar;s, and rayse vpe thi
herte and syng wit&hbar; &thorn;a&mtail;, Gloria in excelsis Deo,
&amp;c.  Of &thorn;e passio&ntail; sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke how
&thorn;at He was at swylke a ty&mtail; of &thorn;e nyghte betrayed by
His descyple, and take&ntail; als a traytoure, and bownde&ntail; als a
thefe, and ledde als a felo&ntail;.</P>

<P>&para; Be-fore pryme &thorn;ou sa&llbar; thynke of &thorn;e
passio&ntail; of Ihesu and of His Ioyfu&llbar; ryssynge.  Of His
passyo&ntail; sa&llbar; &thorn;ou thynke how &thorn;e Iewes led&dtail;
Hym into &thorn;aire counsaile, and bare false wytnes agayne Hym, and
put appone Hym &thorn;at He had saide blasefeme, &thorn;at es,
sclandyre in God&dtail;, and &thorn;at He had said &thorn;at He suld
haue distroyede &thorn;e temple of God&dtail;, and make agayne
ano&thorn;er with-in the thirde day; and &thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay
byga&ntail; to dryfe Hym ti&llbar; hethyng, and to fulle Hym als a
fule, and spite one Hy&mtail; in dispyte in His faire face; and
sythy&ntail; thay hide His eghe&ntail;, and gafe Hy&mtail; bofetes
grete, and sythe&ntail; asked Hy&mtail; whate He was &thorn;at Hym
<PB N="43">



smate; and sythe&ntail;, &thorn;ay ledde Hym dreryly to &thorn;e
dede,  <MILESTONE N="207" UNIT="leaf">and &yogh;itt neuer He sayde ti&llbar; thaym anes why
&thorn;ay swa dyde.  Many othyre wykkydnes &thorn;ay dide Hym,
&thorn;at lange ware to telle.  &YOGH;itt before pryme sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou thynke of &thorn;e haly rysesynge, &thorn;at at &thorn;at
tyme of &thorn;e daye Ihesu Ioyfully rase fra dede to lyfe, whe&ntail;
&thorn;at He hade destruyede helle and delyuerede haly sawles owte of
