flesche and His blude in liknes of brede and of wyne, for to
comfort&hbar;e oure bodily witte thurghe swylke fude als we ere wounte
for to see, and alswa for to helpe oure trouthe thurghe &thorn;at,
&thorn;at we see a thynge and trowes ano&thorn;er.  And
&thorn;are-fore, dere frende, whe&ntail; &thorn;ou sa&llbar; gaa for
to reschaife &thorn;at swete flesche and &thorn;at blude of Ihesu thi
saueour, luke at &thorn;ou haue verray contricyo&ntail;, and
repentance, and clensynge of thi sy&ntail; in thi herte; For
&thorn;are &thorn;ou ressayfes in sacrament reghte als &thorn;ou
ressayfede Hy&mtail; in flesche and blude &mdash; blescede be
&thorn;at grace! &para; Be-fore comply&ntail; sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
thynke how &thorn;at Iosep&hbar; and Nicodemus wande  <MILESTONE
N="208" UNIT="leaf"> Ihesu body
in faire schetis, and enoynte it with precyouse oynementes, and laide
it in a monumente of stane, and sett &thorn;aire seles apo&ntail;
&thorn;e stane, and knyghtes &thorn;at sulde it kepe.  The to&thorn;er
thynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou sa&llbar; thynke in &thorn;e same tyme es
&thorn;is, how Ihesus, in &thorn;e daye of supere, when He had
souppede, He &yogh;ode in-ti&llbar; a gardy&ntail; with His discyples,
and felle downe in Orysou&ntail;, and bygan&ntail; for


 
<!-- 0024.p46-47.txt -->
<PB N="46">


to swete one swilke manere &thorn;at &thorn;e droppis of blode
droppede of His blyssede face vn-ti&llbar; &thorn;e erthe.  Now hase
&thorn;ou matire and manere for to thynke of Goddis manhede.  And
eftirwarde sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wit how &thorn;ou sa&llbar; thynke one
Hym in His heghe Godhede.  &para; To &thorn;at sa&llbar; &thorn;ou wit
&thorn;at Godd temper&dtail; swa His knaweynge fra &thorn;e begynnynge
of mankynde, &thorn;at He walde noghte a&llbar; hally schewe Hym to
ma&ntail;, ne a&llbar; hally hele Hy&mtail; fra ma&ntail;. For if He
hade a&llbar; hally schewede Hym to ma&ntail;, &thorn;an had&dtail;
trouthe noghte bene worthe and mysbileue had noghte bene
&thorn;a&ntail; ouercome&ntail;, For trouthe es of thynge &thorn;at
may noghte be sene; &thorn;an &thorn;at at I see es noghte trouthe ;
and if He had a&llbar; hallily helede fra ma&ntail;, &thorn;an had
trouthe noghte bene helpede, and mysbileue hade bene excusede; and
for-&thorn;i &thorn;a&ntail; walde He in party schewe Hy&mtail;, and
in party hele Hy&mtail;.  Bot now may &thorn;ou aske me, `in how many
maners He walde schewe Hy&mtail;.'  I say in twa maners, ane
wit&hbar;-in, ano&thorn;er wit&hbar;-owtte&ntail;.  With-in He
schewede Hy&mtail; thurgh reuelacyo&ntail; and thurgh
reson&ntail;. With-owtte&ntail;, thurg&hbar; halye writte and
thurg&hbar; creaturs.  Thurg&hbar; reuelacyo&ntail;, whe&ntail; He
schewede Hym ti&llbar; any folke thurg&hbar; inspiracio&ntail; and
thurghe myracle.  By reson&ntail;, commes He ti&llbar; &thorn;e
knawynge of ma&ntail; one &thorn;is manere : &mdash; Ilke a ma&ntail;
may wele see in hym-selfe &thorn;at at he es, and &thorn;at at he hase
bene, bot he may wele wit &thorn;at he hase noghte bene ay, and for
&thorn;at he wate wele &thorn;at su&mtail; ty&mtail; he be-ga&ntail;
for to be; &thorn;an was &thorn;aire su&mtail; ty&mtail; whe&ntail; he
was noghte.  Bot whe&ntail; he was noghte, &thorn;an moghte he one na
wyese make hy&mtail;-selfe; and &thorn;is seghes ma&ntail; in his
creature, For he sees ilke a day su&mtail; ga and su&mtail; co&mtail;,
For-&thorn;i, se&ntail; ilke thynges erre, and &thorn;ay erre noghte
of thay&mtail; selfe, &thorn;are-fore it behoues nede &thorn;at
&thorn;are be ane to gyffe a&llbar; thynges to be, &thorn;at es to
saye of whaym alle thynges are; &thorn;are-fore it behoues of force
&thorn;at He thurg&hbar;e whaym alle thynges erre, be
with-owtte&ntail; begynnynge.  For if He hade begynnyng, tha&ntail; it
behoufede &thorn;at He had begynnyng of su&mtail; o&thorn;er;
&thorn;a&ntail; had He noghte bene &thorn;e first autour and &thorn;e
fyrste begynnyng of a&llbar; thyngez.  Bot &thorn;are was na thynge
before Hy&mtail;, &thorn;an he come of na no&thorn;er, &thorn;a&ntail;
hade He neuer na begynnynge.
<PB N="47">


And &thorn;are-fore it behoufes one a&llbar; maner of &thorn;e werlde,
&thorn;at &thorn;are be a thynge &thorn;at neuer hade begynnynge.  And
whe&ntail; reso&ntail; of ma&ntail; sese of force &thorn;at it may na
no&thorn;er wysse be, &thorn;an he begynnys for to trowe stabilly
&thorn;at a thynge &thorn;at was with-owtte&ntail; begynnynge,
&thorn;at es Awtour, and makere, and gouernere of a&llbar; thynges
&thorn;at ere.  And Hym calles me&ntail; God&dtail; by This skill, For
&thorn;is worde Deus, &thorn;at es to say, God&dtail;, commes of a
worde of grewe &thorn;at es called theos, and &thorn;at es  <MILESTONE
N="208 bk." UNIT="leaf"> als
meki&llbar; for to say als ane anely God&dtail;.  And &thorn;at
betakyns &thorn;is worde God&dtail;.</P>

<P>And, dere frend, &thorn;ou awe to wit &thorn;at &thorn;are ne es
bot a God&dtail;, and &thorn;ou awe to wit &thorn;at na gude may faile
to God&dtail;.  Bot for-&thorn;i &thorn;at swete thynge and gud thynge
es comforthe of felaschepe, &thorn;an may noghte God&dtail; be
with-owtte&ntail; gudnes of felaschipe.  Than be-houede it nede
&thorn;at &thorn;are ware many persones in God&dtail;, &thorn;e
hegheste gudnes.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at felyschepe may noghte be
be-twyx faere &thorn;a&ntail; twa, &thorn;are-fore be-houes it be
&thorn;at in God&dtail; be at &thorn;e leste twa persones. And
for-&thorn;i &thorn;at felyschipe es litti&llbar; worthe whare
&thorn;are es na&ntail; Alyance ne lufe, For-thi it behoues &thorn;at
&thorn;e thirde perso&ntail; ware in God&dtail;, &thorn;at ware the
Alyance and &thorn;e lufe be-twyx the twa.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at
anehede es gude, and manyhede alswa, &thorn;are-fore it behouede nede
&thorn;at anehede and manyhede bathe ware in God&dtail;.  And by
&thorn;is ski&llbar; commes ma&ntail; to &thorn;e knaweynge of
God&dtail;, &thorn;at He es a God&dtail; in Hy&mtail;selfe, and thre
in persones.  And &thorn;is ilke may ma&ntail; see in hym-selfe, For
he sese at &thorn;e begynnynge &thorn;at he hase in hym-selfe Powere,
and sythe&ntail; eftir powere he hase wysdo&mtail;.  And sythe&ntail;
be-gane he for to lufe &thorn;at wysdo&mtail;; and &thorn;an begynnes
he for to knawe apertely &thorn;at &thorn;are es in &thorn;e saule
Mighte, and of &thorn;at myghte commes wysdo&mtail;, and of thayme
bathe comes lufe.  And when ma&ntail; sese &thorn;at it es one swylke
manere in hym, Of &thorn;at awe hy&mtail; to wit &thorn;at one swylke
ma&ntail; awe it to be in God&dtail; &thorn;at es aboue&ntail;
hy&mtail;, &thorn;at es to say, &thorn;at in God&dtail; es myghte, and
of &thorn;at commes his wysdo&mtail;e; and of powere and wysedo&mtail;
bathe comes lufe.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at of &thorn;e fyrste
personne commes &thorn;e to&thorn;er, and owte of thay&mtail; bathe
comes &thorn;e thyrde, For-thi calles he &thorn;e firste personne
God&dtail; &thorn;e Fadire, &thorn;e to&thorn;er God&dtail; &thorn;e
Sonne, &thorn;e thirde



<!-- 0025.p48-49.txt -->
<PB N="48">


God&dtail; &thorn;e Haly Gaste.  And for &thorn;at it wounte to be
thus inmanges me&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;e Fadir was mare Febi&llbar;
&thorn;an &thorn;e sonne, for his elde, and &thorn;e sonne mare vnwyse
&thorn;an &thorn;e Fadire for his &yogh;outhe; and for &thorn;at a man
sulde noghte wene &thorn;at it ware swa of God&dtail;, Tharefore es
powere appropirde to God&dtail; &thorn;e Fadir, wysdo&mtail; to
God&dtail; &thorn;e Sonne.  And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;is worde
Gaste sownnes sumwhate into fellenes, For-&thorn;i es swetnes, lufe,
and gudenes appropirde to &thorn;e Haly Gaste. Oppo&ntail; &thorn;is
maner commes ma&ntail; firste to &thorn;e knaweynge of his God&dtail;,
how He es with-owtte&ntail; be-gynnynge, and whi He es called
God&dtail;, ane in substance and thre in persones, and whi &thorn;e
firste persone es callede God&dtail; &thorn;e Fadir, &thorn;e
to&thorn;er, God&dtail; &thorn;e Sonne, &thorn;e thyrde, God&dtail;
&thorn;e Haly Gaste; and whi powere es appropirde to God&dtail;
&thorn;e Fadir, and wysdo&mtail; to God&dtail; &thorn;e Sonne, and
gudnes to God&dtail; &thorn;e Haly Gaste.  In swylke manere sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou knawe &thorn;i God&dtail;.</P>

<P>The fyrste degre of contemplacio&ntail; es, &thorn;at &thorn;e
saule be ledde agayne to &thorn;e selfe, and gedire it a&llbar;
with-in &thorn;e selfe.  The to&thorn;er degre es, &thorn;at man see
whate he es, swa gedyrde to-gedire.  The thirde degre es, &thorn;at he
lefte hym selfe abouen hym-selfe, <MILESTONE N="209" UNIT="leaf">and payne hym for to luke one
his God&dtail; in his awe&ntail; kynde.  Bot ti&llbar; selfe may he
neuer mare comme, vnti&llbar; he hafe lerede to resayfe ilke a bodyly
ymagynacyone erthely and gastely, &thorn;at commes to his awe&ntail;
herte, ow&thorn;er of herynge, or of tastynge, or of sweloynge, or of
any o&thorn;er bodily wite, to refuse it and to defule it, &thorn;at
it may see the selfe swylke as it es with-owtte&ntail; &thorn;e bodye.
Thare-fore, dere Frende, take gud hede how &thorn;e saule es
wondirfu&llbar; in &thorn;e selfe, and howe it es ane in &thorn;e
kynde, and noghte forthi &yogh;it it duse dyuerse thynges; For
&thorn;e selfe, it sese &thorn;at at &thorn;ou sese with thy&ntail;
eghne, heris with thyne eres, Swelawes with thi mouthe, Smelles with
&thorn;i nese, and al swa &thorn;at at &thorn;ou touches with a&llbar;
&thorn;i membris.  &para; Thynke &yogh;it Eftyrwarde, howe &thorn;i
saule es grete, &thorn;at a&llbar; anely with a thoghte it may
comprehende heue&ntail; and ert&hbar;e and a&llbar; &thorn;at in
thay&mtail; are, if &thorn;ay ware a hundret&hbar; falde grettere
&thorn;a&ntail; &thorn;ay are or may be.  &para; When manes lyfe es
grete and swa nobi&llbar; &thorn;at na creature may
<PB N="49">



vndirstande it perfitly, Thane grete and nobi&llbar; es he &thorn;at
swa nobi&llbar; thynge made of noghte.  He es aboue&ntail; a&llbar;
thynge, and with-in all thynge, and with-owtte&ntail; all thynge, and
be-net&hbar;e a&llbar; thynge.  He is aboue&ntail; a&llbar; thynge,
a&llbar; thynge gouernande, Be-net&hbar;e a&llbar; thynge, berande
a&llbar; thynge, with-in a&llbar; thynge, Fulfillande a&llbar;,
with-owtte&ntail; a&llbar; thynge, abowte gangande a&llbar;.</P>

<P>&para; Swylke manere of contemplacione Engendyrs in ma&ntail; Faste
trouthe and sekire deuocyone. &para; Eftir &thorn;is sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou thynke howe &thorn;at he es large: and &thorn;at may
&thorn;ou see one many maners.  See at &thorn;e begynnynge howe
&thorn;at he es large of erthely gude; how he gyfes his gudes als wele
to &thorn;e i&llbar;e als to &thorn;e gude in alle thynges &thorn;at
&thorn;ou sese in erthe.  Sythe&ntail; eftirwar&dtail; see howe
&thorn;at he es large for to Forgyffe: For if a mane hym ane hade
donne a&llbar;s meki&llbar; i&llbar;e als a&llbar;e &thorn;e men of
&thorn;is werlde moghte doo, &yogh;itt sulde he be mare redy be
&thorn;e hundrethe parte for to Forgyffe hym &thorn;an &thorn;at
caytife sulde bee for to aske of hym forgyfenes.</P>

<P>&para; Nowe, my dere Frende, if &thorn;ou lyfe eftir &thorn;is
kennynge, &thorn;an sa&llbar; &thorn;ou lyfe honourabily, &mdash; and
&thorn;at es &thorn;e fyrste parte of oure sermo&ntail; &thorn;at I
touchede at &thorn;e begynnynge, &mdash; and eftir &thorn;at sa&llbar;
&thorn;ou studye to lyffe lufely als to thyne euencryste&ntail;; and
vnti&llbar; &thorn;at sa&llbar; &thorn;ou sette a&llbar; hally
&thorn;i myghte to lufe and for to be lufede.  Thou sa&llbar; lufe
a&llbar; menne in God&dtail;, &thorn;at es at say, anely in gudnes,
and noghte for &thorn;aire fairenes of bodye for to lufe, ne for
force, ne for na no&thorn;er bodily vertu.  For &thorn;ay &thorn;at
lufes in swylke manere, &thorn;ay lufe noghte for Goddes sake; and for
to lufe ma&ntail; in God&dtail; es na no&thorn;er thynge bot for to
lufe hy&mtail; for any thynge &thorn;at may noghte be lufede
with-owtte&ntail; God&dtail;, als for gudnes or for rightewysnes, or
for sothefastenes.  If we do gude, &thorn;ane hafe we na frende bot
gude, ne nane Enemy bot i&llbar;; and &thorn;ar-fore &thorn;ase
&thorn;at er gude sa&llbar; we lufe, for-thi &thorn;at &thorn;ay er
gude, and &thorn;e ille sa&llbar; we lufe for-&thorn;i &thorn;at
&thorn;ay may be gude.  In &thorn;is manere lufe &thorn;ou na thynge
bot gudnes, se&ntail; &thorn;at &thorn;ou lufes a&llbar; thynges for
gudnes; and if &thorn;ou wi&llbar; be lufede, schewe thi selfe lufely.
Ife &thorn;ou wi&llbar; be lufely, resayfe these thre wordes
with-owtte&ntail; forgetynge.  Do &thorn;at at man biddis &thorn;e or
praies &thorn;e &thorn;at gude es; Take &thorn;at at ma&ntail; gyffes
&thorn;e; and gruche noghte;


 
<!-- 0026.p50-51.txt -->
<PB N="50">


and &thorn;at at men wi&llbar; say &thorn;e, suffire it mekely, and
wrethe the noghte.  If &thorn;ou lyfe &thorn;us lelely, &thorn;an
lyfes thou lufely.</P>

<P>Dere Syster and frende, Sye&ntail; eftirwarde sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
studye for to lyffe mekely; and to &thorn;is sa&llbar; &thorn;ou
ow&ntail; wit &thorn;at &thorn;are are twa maners of mekenes.  The
tane commes of sothefastenes, and &thorn;e to&thorn;er commes of
charite.<MILESTONE N="209 bk." UNIT="leaf">    By &thorn;e firste may &thorn;ou hafe knaweynge of thi
selfe, For thou may noghte in na manere of &thorn;is worlde see
&thorn;i selfe whate &thorn;ou arte in sothefastenes, if &thorn;ou be
noghte mekyde.  The to&thorn;er manere of meknes may &thorn;ou hafe if
thou thynke of &thorn;e meknes of Ihesu Criste, how &thorn;at he mekid
hym &thorn;at neuer dyde sy&ntail; ; and swylke mekenes commes clenely
of charyte.</P>

<P>&para; Now, my dere syster and Frende, wate &thorn;ou whate it es
to lyffe honourabili, lufely, and mekely; and &thorn;at es to lyffe
perfitly.  Now oure swete Lorde Ihesu Criste gyffe vs grace, swa
God&dtail; for to honour, and oure euencriste&ntail; for to lufe, and
oure selfe for to meke, &thorn;at we may for oure honourynge be
honourede, and for oure lufe be lufede, and for oure mekenes be
lyftede vp in-to &thorn;e heghe blysse of heue&ntail; &thorn;at he
boghte vs to, Ihesu with his swete blude and his preciouse
passio&ntail;. Ame&ntail;!</P>

<P><CORR SIC="expliculum" RESP="Perry">Explicit</CORR> speculum sancti Edmundi Cantuarensis Archiepiscopi.  Dulce
nomen Domini nostri Ihesu Christi: sit benedictum in secula seculorum!
Ame&ntail; !</P></DIV1>
<PB N="51">

<DIV1 TYPE="tract">
<HEAD TYPE="main">III. THE ABBEY OF THE HOLY GHOST.</HEAD>

<MILESTONE
ED="Robert Thornton's MS., Lincoln Cathedral Library." N="271" UNIT="leaf">

<HEAD>RELIGIO Sancti SPiritus.  RELIGIO MUNDA.</HEAD>

<HEAD>OFF the abbaye of saynte Spirite, that es in a place that es
callede conscyence.</HEAD>

<P>A, dere brethir and systirs ! I see &thorn;at many walde be in
religyo&ntail;, bot &thorn;ay may noghte, owthir for pouerte, or for
drede of thaire ky&ntail;, or for band of Maryage; and for-thi I make
- here a buke of &thorn;e religeon of &thorn;e herte, &thorn;at es, of
&thorn;e abbaye of the Holy Goste, that a&llbar; tho &thorn;at ne may
noghte be bodyly in religyo&ntail;, &thorn;at &thorn;ay may be
gostely.  A, Ihesu, Mercy! whare may &thorn;is abbay beste be funded,
and &thorn;is religione ?  Now certis nowhare so wele als in a place
&thorn;at es called `conscyence'; and who so wi&llbar; be besy to
funde &thorn;is holy religio&ntail;, and &thorn;at may ilke gud
crysty&ntail; ma&ntail; and woman do, &thorn;at wi&llbar; be besy
&thorn;er- abowte.  And at &thorn;e begynnynge it es by-houely
&thorn;at &thorn;e place of thi conscience be clensed clene of
sy&ntail;; to &thorn;e whilke clensynge &thorn;e Haly Goste sa&llbar;
sende two maydyns &thorn;at ere conande: the one es callede `
rightwysnes,' and &thorn;e to&thorn;er is called `luffe of clennes.'
Thiese two sa&llbar; cast fro &thorn;e conscience and fro &thorn;e
herte, all maner of fylthe of foule thoghtes and desyris.  Whe&ntail;
&thorn;e place of &thorn;e conscience es wele clensed, than sa&llbar;
&thorn;e grownde be mad lange and depe; and thies two maydenes
sa&llbar; be made, &thorn;e one es callede `Mekenes,' &thorn;at
sa&llbar; make &thorn;e grownde depe thorowe lowlynes of hir selfe,
the to&thorn;er es callede `Pouerte,' i &thorn;at makis it large &
wyde abowne, &thorn;at castis ouer ylke a halfe &thorn;e erthe owte,
&thorn;at es to say, alle erthely lustes & worldely thoghtes ferre fro
&thorn;e herte, &thorn;at, if &thorn;ay hase erthely gudis, with luffe
&thorn;ay for-gete &thorn;ay&mtail; for &thorn;e ty&mtail;, & castis
no lufe to &thorn;a&mtail;, nor hase noghte, ne settis noghte for
&thorn;at tyme &thorn;aire hertes no thynge one &thorn;a&mtail;.  And
thies ere called `pure in spyrite,' of wha&mtail; God spekes in
&thorn;e gospelle, & sayse &thorn;at `thaires es &thorn;e


 
<!-- 0027.p52-53.txt -->
<PB N="52">


kyngdo&mtail; of heue&ntail;, be thies wordes Beati pauperes spiritu,
quoniam ipsorum est regnum * ` coelorum.  Blyssed es &thorn;a&ntail;
&thorn;at religyo&ntail; &thorn;at es funndide in pouerte and in
meknes.  This es agaynes many religyous &thorn;at are couetous and
prowde.</P>

<P>This abbaye also sa&llbar; be sett on a gud reuer, and &thorn;at
sa&llbar; be &thorn;e reuer of teres.  For swylke abbayes &thorn;at
ere sett one swylke gude ryuers, &thorn;ay are wele at ese, and
&thorn;e more dylecyous duellyng es &thorn;er.  <MILESTONE
N="271 bk." UNIT="leaf">One swylke a reuer
was Mary Mawdelayne fowndide, For-thy grace and rechesse come a&llbar;
to hir wi&llbar;, and for-thi sayde Dauid thus, Fluminis impetus
letificat ciuitatem, &thorn;at es to saye, `the gude reuer mase
&thorn;e Cete lykande,' for it es clene sekyr, & ryche of a&llbar;
gude marchandyse.  And so &thorn;e reuer of teris clenses Goddis cete,
&thorn;at es, mannes saule, &thorn;at es Goddes cete.  And also
&thorn;e holy man sayse of fylthe of syn&ntail;, &thorn;at it brynges
owte &thorn;e reches of vertus and of alle gude thewes.  And when
&thorn;is grownde es made, &thorn;an sa&llbar; come a dameselle,
Bowsomnes, on &thorn;e tone halfe, and dameselle Miserecorde one
&thorn;e to&thorn;er halfe, for to rayse &thorn;e walles one heghte,
and to make &thorn;am stalworthe, with a fre hert largely gyfande to
&thorn;e pure, & to &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at myster hase. For
whe&ntail; we do any gud werkes of charite thorow &thorn;e grace of
Gode, als ofte sythis als we &thorn;am do in &thorn;e lufe and
&thorn;e louynge of God, and in gud Entent, als many gud stonys we
laye one owre howssynge in &thorn;e blysse of heue&ntail;, festenande
togedir with &thorn;e lufe of Gode and oure eue&ntail;-cryste&ntail;.
We rede &thorn;at Salomo&ntail; made his howssynge of gret precyouse
stones.  Thiese precyous stones are almos-dedis and werkes of mercy, &
holy werkes &thorn;at sa&llbar; be bownde&ntail; to-gedir with qwyke
lyme of lufe & stedfaste by-leue.  And for-thi sayse Dauid, Omnia
opera eius in fide, &thorn;at es to saye, `alle his werkes be done in
stedfaste by-leue.'  And als a walle maye not laste with-owtte&ntail;
syment, or more, also no werkes &thorn;at we wyrke, are noghte worthe
to God, nor spedfu&llbar; ti&llbar; oure sawles, bot &thorn;ay be done
in the lufe of God and in trewe by-leue. For alle &thorn;at &thorn;e
synfu&llbar; dose, a&llbar;e es loste.  Sythe&ntail; Dameselle
Sufferance and damese&llbar; Forte sa&llbar; rayse &thorn;e pelars, &
vndirsett &thorn;a&mtail; so strangly, &thorn;at no wynde of wordes,
<PB N="53">


angre of stryffe, fleschely nor gastely, sowre ne swete, caste
&thorn;a&mtail; downe.  A, dere brethir and systers, &yogh;itt
by-houys &thorn;e cloystyre be made one foure corners; and it es
callede cloyster' for it closys and steskys, and warely sa&llbar; be
lokkede.  My dere bre&thorn;ir and systyrs, wylke of &yogh;ow as
wi&llbar; halde this gastely religyo&ntail;, & be in ryste of sawle &
in swetnes of hert, halde &thorn;e with-i&ntail; &thorn;e cloyster,
and so sparre &thorn;ou &thorn;e &yogh;ates, and so warely kepe
&thorn;ou &thorn;e wardes of &thorn;i cloyster, &thorn;at no
no&thorn;er fand- yngez nor euy&llbar;e styrrynges hafe in-gate in
the, & make &thorn;at thy Sylence, <MILESTONE N="272" UNIT="leaf">and for to [ ] the, or styrre the
to syn&ntail; <NOTE ID="n8">There is some confusion in this sentence from the omission of one or more words.</NOTE> steke thy&ntail; eghne fro fowle syghtes, thy&ntail;
heres fro foule herynges, thy Mouthe fro foule speche, and thy&ntail;
herte fra foule thoghtes.  Scrifte sa&llbar; [make] thi chapitir,
Predicacio&ntail; sa&llbar; make thi fratour, Oracio&ntail; sa&llbar;
make thi chape&llbar;e, Con- templacione sa&llbar; make thi dortoure,
&thorn;at sa&llbar; be raysede one heghte with heghe &yogh;ernynge,
and with lufe qwykkynynge to Gode, and &thorn;at sa&llbar; be owte ofe
worldly noyse and of worldly angyrse and besynes, als fere furthe als
&thorn;ou may for &thorn;e ty&mtail; thorow grace for &thorn;e
ty&mtail; of prayere.  Contemplacio&ntail; es a deuote rysynge of
herte with byrnynge lufe to God to do wele, and in his delites Ioyes
his saule, and somdele ressayves of that swetnes &thorn;at Goddis
chose&ntail; childir sa&llbar; hafe in heue&ntail;.  Rewfulnes
sa&llbar; make the fermorye, Deuocio&ntail; sa&llbar; make &thorn;e
celere, Meditacion sa&llbar; make the gernere.</P>

<P>And when a&llbar; &thorn;e howses bene made, &thorn;an be-houes
&thorn;e Holy Gaste Ordeyne &thorn;e couent of grace & of vertu.  And
&thorn;an sa&llbar; &thorn;e Holy Gaste &thorn;at &thorn;is religyone
es of, bee warde&ntail; and visiture, the whilke God &thorn;e Fadir
funded thorow his powere.  For &thorn;us saise Dauide, Fundauit eam
altissimus, and this es to saye, `the heghe Gode &thorn;e Fadyr
Fundide this relegyone.'  The So&ntail; thurg&hbar; his wysedo&mtail;
&thorn;an ordayned it, als Sayne Paule witnes it, Que adeo ordinata
sunt, &thorn;at es at saye, `a&llbar;e &thorn;at es of God the Sone,
it rewlis & ordaynes.'  The Holy Goste &yogh;emys it and vesettes it;
and &thorn;at saye [we] in holy kyrke whe&ntail; we saye &thorn;is,

 
<!-- 0028.p54-55.txt -->
<PB N="54">


Veni Creator Spiritus, with Qui paraclitus diceris, &thorn;at es for
to saye, `come, &thorn;ou God &thorn;e Haly Gaste, and thyne &thorn;ou
vesete, and fulfi&llbar; &thorn;a&mtail; with grace.'  And than the
gude lady Charite, als scho &thorn;at es most worthy by-fore alle
o&thorn;er, sa&llbar; be abbas of this sely abbaye.  And also, als
&thorn;ay &thorn;at are in relegyone sa&llbar; do no thynge, ne saye
thynge, ne gange in-to no stede, ne take no gyfte, with-owtte&ntail;
leue of &thorn;e abbasse.  Also gastely sa&llbar; none of swylke
thyngys be done with-owtte&ntail; leue of charite, For thus commandes
Sayne Paule, Omnia vestra in caritate fiant, &thorn;at es, ` what-so
&yogh;e do, or saye, or thynke with herte, alle &yogh;e mon do in
charite.'  A, dere bre&thorn;ir and systirs, whate here es harde
eomandement ! Bot it es noghte fu&llbar; i&llbar; to oure sawles
&thorn;at oure thoghtes & oure wordes & oure werkes be onely done for
lufe.  Wayleawaye! if I durste saye! for many are in religione, bot to
fewe relegious, &thorn;at &thorn;ay ne done &thorn;e comandment of
saynte Paule, or &thorn;e conce&llbar;e of &thorn;e <MILESTONE
N="272 bk." UNIT="leaf">gud lady
Charite, &thorn;at 1 es abbesse of this cely relegyo&ntail;.  And
for-thi &thorn;ay lose meki&llbar; ty&mtail;, and losses &thorn;aire
mede, and ekes thaire payne gretly, bot if &thorn;ay amende &thorn;am,
whare-fore, leue bre&thorn;ir and systirs, bese euer-more wakire and
warre; and in a&llbar; &yogh;oure werkes, thynke depely &thorn;at
whate-so &yogh;ee doo, be it done in &thorn;e lufe of Gode, and for
&thorn;e lufe of &thorn;e lady Wysdome &thorn;at sa&llbar; be
prioresse; for scho es worth i, Nam, pr ior omnium creata est
sapiencia, &thorn;at es, `al-&thorn;ir-firste es Wysedcoe made'; and
thurg&hbar; &thorn;e lare of hir, and &thorn;e concele cf &thorn;is
prioresse, sa&llbar; we do alle &thorn;at we do; and this sayse Dauid,
Omnia in sapiencia fecisti, &thorn;at es at saye, `alle &thorn;at
&thorn;ou hase made, &thorn;ou hase made wysely.'  The gud lady Meknes
&thorn;at aye Elyke makis hir selfe lowly and vndir alle o&thorn;er,
sa&llbar; be supprioresse: hir sa&llbar; &yogh;e honoure and wirchipe
with bouxomnes.  A Ihesu! blyssede &thorn;at abbaye, and cely es
&thorn;at religyone, &thorn;at hase so haly ane abbas as Charyte, a
prioresse as Wysedome, a supprioresse as Mekenes.  A, dere
bre&thorn;ir and systirs, blyssede and Cely are &thorn;ay, &thorn;at
es to say, those saules are eely &thorn;at haldis &thorn;e comandment
of &thorn;e abbas lady Charite, and &thorn;e techynge of &thorn;e
priores, lady Wysdome, and the concele of &thorn;e suppriorese, lady
mekenes; For who-so es bouxome to
<PB N="55">


thir thre ladyse, and &thorn;aire lyffe rewlis aftir &thorn;aire
techynge, the Fadir, the Sone, the Holy Goste, &thorn;am sa&llbar;
comfurthe with many gostely Ioyes, and &thorn;am helpe and socoure in
alle fandinges, in angirs, &thorn;at &thorn;ay ne be noghte
ouercome&ntail;; &thorn;am thare drede no wrenkis ne no wylis of the
fende, for why God es with &thorn;a&mtail;, and standis aye by
&thorn;a&mtail; als a trewe kepere & a strange.  And for-&thorn;i says
Dauid thus, Dominus protector vite mee, a quo trepidabo ? als if he
sayd, ` God es my champyone staleworthe and trewe, &thorn;at for me,
&thorn;at es so wayke and so vnmyghtfu&llbar;, agaynes my&ntail;
Enemyse hase vndirtane for to fyghte: whame thare me &thorn;a&ntail;
drede ? now trewly, righte none.'  We rede in a buke of Danyele
&thorn;at a myghtfu&llbar; was &thorn;at me&ntail; callede
Nabogodhonosore, &thorn;at sett in Rome thre me&ntail; &thorn;at solde
do & ordayne and staby&llbar;, als baylyes, alle &thorn;e rewme, so
&thorn;at &thorn;e kynge herde no noyse, ne no playnte, bot &thorn;at
he myghte be in pese, & in Ioye, & in ryste in his rewme.  And righte
so &thorn;e rewme of &thorn;e sawle &thorn;at thiese thre baylyes are
I&ntail;, and &thorn;e religione &thorn;at thies thre prelates are
I&ntail;, &thorn;at es, Charite, Wyse- dome and Mekenes, thare es
pese, ryste, and lykynge in saule, and comforthe in lyfe.</P>

<P>Damsele Discrecyone, &thorn;at es witty and be fu&llbar; ware,
sa&llbar; be tresorere; scho sa&llbar; hafe in hir kepynge alle, <MILESTONE
N="273" UNIT="leaf">and
&yogh;ernely luke &thorn;at all go wele.  Orysone salle be
chaunterese, &thorn;at with hertly prayers sa&llbar; trauele daye &
nyghte.  And whate Orysoue es, &thorn;e haly ma&ntail; sayse, Oracio
est Deo sacrificium, angelis solacium, diabolo tormentum, &thorn;at es
to saye, ` Orysone es a lonely sacrafice to God, Solase and
lykynge to Ange&llbar;s, and turment to &thorn;e fende.'  It witnes in
the lyfe of Saynte Barthil- mewe, &thorn;at it es turment to &thorn;e
fende; for &thorn;e fende cryede to hym and sayde Bartholomee !
incendunt me oraciones tue, &thorn;at es to saye, ` Bertilmew, thi
prayers byrnys me.'  And &thorn;at es lykynge to angels, Saynte
Bartilinew wytnes it, and sayse, `whe&ntail; we praye with deuocyone
of hert, the Angels standis byfore, daunsesande & prayeande, and beris
oure prayers vp, and a present of &thorn;a&mtail; to &thorn;e Fadir of
heue&ntail;.  &THORN;e whilke prayers oure Lorde commandes to wryte in
&thorn;e buke of lyfe, &thorn;at es,


 
<!-- 0029.p56-57.txt -->
<PB N="56">


sacrafyce to God: this are of &thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at hym moste
payes; and for-thi he askes vs it &thorn;er he sayse thus, Sacrificium
1audis honorificabis me, &thorn;at es to saye, `&yogh;e salle wyrchipe
wit&hbar; sacrifice of louynge.'  Iubilacio hir felowe sa&llbar;
helpe; and, what Iubilacio&ntail; es, a seynt it telles, and sayse
&thorn;at Iubylacio&ntail; es a grete Ioye &thorn;at es consayuede in
teris, thorow brynnande luffe of spirite, &thorn;at may noghte be in
a&llbar; schewede, no in alle hyde, als it fallis somtyme of tho
&thorn;at God hertly lufes: &thorn;ere- eftir &thorn;at &thorn;ay hafe
bene in prayere and in orysone, &thorn;ay ere so lyghte & so lykande
in God &thorn;at, whare-so &thorn;ay go, &thorn;er hertes synges
murnynge songes of lufe-longynge to &thorn;aire lefe, &thorn;at
&thorn;ay &yogh;erne with armys of lufe semlyly to falde, and with
gastely mourny[n]ge of his gudnes swetly to kysse, and &yogh;it
vmwhile so depely, &thorn;at wordis &thorn;am wanttis, for
luf-longynge so ferforthe rauesches thorow hertis, &thorn;at
somty&mtail; &thorn;ay ne wote noghte whate &thorn;ay do.  Deuocione
es celeresse, &thorn;at kepis &thorn;e wynnes, bothe &thorn;e white
and &thorn;e rede, with depe vmbythynkynge of &thorn;e gudnes of God,
& of &thorn;e paynnes & of &thorn;e anguyse &thorn;at he tholede, and
of the Ioyes & &thorn;e delytes of paradyse, &thorn;at he hase
ordayned to his chose&ntail;.  Penance sa&llbar; be kychynnere,
&thorn;at with grete besynes trayue&llbar;s daye & nyghte for to plese
a&llbar;e, and ofte swetis with bitter teris for angyre of hir synnes.
Scho makes gud metis, &thorn;at es, many bitter sorowes alle for hir
gyltez.  And <MILESTONE N="273 bk." UNIT="leaf"> theys metis fedis &thorn;e saule, bot scho sparis
hir-selfe thorow abstynence, and etys bot litti&llbar;; For, do scho
neuer so meki&llbar; ne so mony-folde of gude werkes, ay semys scho
hir-selfe vnworthy and synfu&llbar;.  Atemperance seruede in the
fratour &thorn;at scho to ylkone so lukes &thorn;at mesure be ouer
alle, &thorn;at none ouer meki&llbar; nere ouer lytti&llbar; ete ne
drynke.  Sobirnes redis at &thorn;e borde the lyues of the haly
Fadirs, and synges and reherces whate lyfe &thorn;at &thorn;ay lede
for to take gud Ensampi&llbar;e to do als &thorn;ay dyd, and
&thorn;ere thorowe slyke mede to wy&ntail; als &thorn;ay now hafe.
Pete es spensere, &thorn;at dose seruesse to gud, a&llbar; &thorn;at
scho maye.  And Mercy hir syster sa&llbar; be ambynowre, &thorn;at
gyffes to a&llbar;e, and noghte kane kepe to hir-selfe.  The lady
Drede es portere, &thorn;at kepis besyly &thorn;e cloyster of &thorn;e
herte, & of &thorn;e conscience
<PB N="57">



&thorn;at chases owte alle vnthewes, and calles In alle gud vertus, &
so speres &thorn;e &yogh;atis of &thorn;e cloyster & &thorn;e wyndows,
&thorn;at none evy&llbar;e hafe none Ingate to &thorn;e herte, thorowe
&thorn;e &yogh;atis of &thorn;e mouthe, ne thorowe &thorn;e wyndows of
&thorn;e eghne, nere of &thorn;e eris.  Honeste es Maystresse of
&thorn;e nouyce, and teches &thorn;am alle curtasye, bow &thorn;ay
sa&llbar; speke and gange, and sytt and stande, and how &thorn;ay
sa&llbar; bere &thorn;a&mtail; with-owtte&ntail; and with-i&ntail;;
howe to God, how to ma&ntail;, so &thorn;at alle &thorn;at
&thorn;a&mtail; sese, of &thorn;am may take ensampi&llbar; of alle
gudnes, and alle gude thewes.  Dameselle Curtasye sa&llbar; be
hostelere; & &thorn;at &thorn;ay comande & byddes, &thorn;at scho
sa&llbar; &thorn;am resafe hendely, so &thorn;at ylke one may speke of
hir.  And for-thi &thorn;at now&thorn;er sa&llbar; be by
&thorn;a&mtail; one enlange the gestes, &mdash; For it myghte falle
&thorn;at dameselle Curtasye solde be oure balde a[nd] ouer hardy,
&mdash; for-thi sa&llbar; scho hafe a felawe Damesele, Symplese; for
&thorn;ay two alyede to-gedir thorowe felawchipe, are sekyre and
semande, for &thorn;e tone with-owtte&ntail; &thorn;e to&thorn;er
vmwhile es litti&llbar; worthe.  For ouer-grete symplesse may make of
&thorn;e symple a sott, or ouer nyce, and ouer-grete curtasye may be
somewhile o&thorn;er to lyghte chere or to glade, or ouer-balde, for
to paye &thorn;e gestes; Bot fayre and wele, & with-owtte&ntail;
fandynge of blame, may &thorn;ay do &thorn;aire Offece both
to-gedir.</P>

<P>Damesele Resone sa&llbar; be puruerere, For scho sa&llbar; ordayne
with-in & with owtty&ntail; so skilfully, &thorn;at &thorn;ere ne be
no defaute.  Damesele Lewte sa&llbar; be fermoresse, &thorn;at
sa&llbar; trauelle abowte, & besely serue &thorn;e seke.  And
for-&thorn;i sen &thorn;at in &thorn;e fermory of this religyo&ntail;
are moo seke &thorn;a&ntail; hole, mo feby&llbar; &thorn;a&ntail;
wighte, and es ouer-grete trauelle to serue &thorn;am alle hyr one, <MILESTONE
N="274" UNIT="leaf">
For-t&hbar;i sa&llbar; scho hafe a felawe, Damesele Largesse,
&thorn;at sa&llbar; see full wele to ylkone after &thorn;at &thorn;am
nedis.  Damesele Conande and Wysse, &thorn;at es callede Meditacyone,
or Poleschesy, es garnere: scho sa&llbar; gedyre and semby&llbar; gude
whete and o&thorn;er gud cornnes to-gedir, and &thorn;at fully, with
grete plente, thorowe &thorn;e whilke alle &thorn;e gud ladyse of
&thorn;e howse may hafe &thorn;aire sustenance.  Meditacio&ntail; es
in gud thoghtes of God, & of his werkes, and of his wordes, and of his
creaturs, and of his paynnens &thorn;at he tholede, and of his grete
lufe &thorn;at he had and hase to &thorn;a&mtail;


 
<!-- 0030.p58-59.txt -->
<PB N="58">


for whay&mtail; he tholede.  This garnere had &thorn;e gud kyng Dauid;
For-&thorn;i was he ay riche & in plente, and for-&thorn;i he sayse in
&thorn;e psaltyre, In omnibus oreribus tuis Meditabar die ac nocte,
&thorn;at es to saye, `Lorde ! in thi lawe I thynke nyghte and daye.
This es begynnynge of a&llbar; perfeccio&ntail;, tha&ntail; whe&ntail;
ma&ntail; settis and staby&llbar;s his herte in depe thynkynge on God
& on his werkes.  For ofte es better a gud thoghte in haly
meditacyo&ntail; &thorn;an Many wordes sayd in prayere, For &thorn;e
holy thoghtes in meditacio&ntail; cryes in Goddes eris.  Ofte it
falles &thorn;at &thorn;e herte es so ouer-tane and so raueschede in
holy meditacyo&ntail;, &thorn;at it wote noghte what it dose, heris,
nor sayse, or seys; so depely es &thorn;e herte festenede in God and
in his werkes, &thorn;at wordis hym wanttis; and &thorn;e stillere
&thorn;at he es in slyke Meditacio&ntail;, the luddere he cryes in
Goddes eris; and &thorn;er-fore sayd Dauid thus, Quoniam tacui dum
clamarem tota die, as if he sayd, `Lorde! lo, here, the whi&llbar;s
my&ntail; herte was in depe thoghtes in the and of thi werkes, it
cryed one the in holy Medytacyons, and was sty&llbar;e, as beynge
domme.'  And &thorn;er sayse &thorn;e glose, `the grete cryes
&thorn;at we crye to God &thorn;an, are oure grete desyres and oure
grete &yogh;ernynges.'  And this sayse Saynte Denyse, &thorn;at sayse,
`When &thorn;e herte es lyfte and raueschede to &thorn;e lufe of God
with gelouse &yogh;ernynges, he ne may sownde with worde &thorn;at
&thorn;e herte thynkis.'  This holy Meditacione, &thorn;at es,
&thorn;e gernare &thorn;at kepis &yogh;erely &thorn;e whete &thorn;at
es rede with-owte and white with-i&ntail;, &thorn;at hase &thorn;e
syde cloue&ntail;, of &thorn;e whilke men mase gud brede, &thorn;at es
called Ihesu Criste, &thorn;at with-owtte&ntail; was rede of his
awe&ntail; blode, and whitte with-i&ntail; tborow his awe&ntail;
mekenes and clennes of lyfe, and hade <MILESTONE N="274 bk." UNIT="leaf"> his syde cloue&ntail; with a
spere, &mdash; this es &thorn;e brede &thorn;at we ressayue and etis in
&thorn;e Sacrament of &thorn;e altyr.  And wele &thorn;ou weite
&thorn;at the gerner sa&llbar; be abow&ntail; &thorn;e Selare, also
sa&llbar; be Meditacio&ntail; before deuocio&ntail;; and for-thi
meditacio&ntail; sa&llbar; be gernare, Deuocio&ntail; Celerrere, and
Pete pene- tancere <NOTE ID="n9">Sic in MS.; but <HI REND="i">?pittancere</HI>, i.e. the officer who served out the rations. The Prioress had charge of the discipline.</NOTE>.  Of thiese thre sayse &thorn;e profete Dauide <NOTE ID="n10">Ps. iv. 8.</NOTE> 
A Fructu frumenti vini, et olei sui, multiplicati sunt, &thorn;at es
at saye, ` Of
<PB N="59">
the fruyte of &thorn;e whete and wyne and oyle, &thorn;ay ere
fulfillede.'  In &thorn;e alde lawe, ;n many stedis, Gode takis to bis
chose&ntail; thiese thre.  `Serue me,' he sayse, `wele, & I sa&llbar;
gyffe &yogh;owe plente of whete and wyne & oyle.'  Plente of whete es,
hertly to thynke one &thorn;e croyce, and euer haffe &thorn;e
passyo&ntail; of Ihesu Crist hertly in mynde.  This es
Meditacio&ntail;.  Plente of wyne, &thorn;at es &thorn;e we&llbar;e of
teres; wele for to wepe, this es Deuocio&ntail;.  Plente of oyle,
&thorn;at es, for to hafe delyte and sauoyre in God; and this es
comforthe, for &thorn;e oyle gyffes odoure to metis, and lyghtes in
&thorn;e kyrke, and byrnys in &thorn;e lampe.  Also whe&ntail; Goddis
seruandes hase depely thoghte with schire herte on Gode, & on his
werkes, with lufe-longynge to &thorn;a&mtail;, &thorn;a&ntail; hase
God pete of &thorn;a&mtail;, and sendis &thorn;am petance of comforthe
and of gastely Ioye; and this gyffes hym at &thorn;e begynnyng
Meditacio&ntail;, and &thorn;is es &thorn;e whete &thorn;at God
hyghttes vs, and deuocyone &thorn;at mea consayues in
medytacyo&ntail;.  Than sendis God sone after &thorn;e wyne, &thorn;at
es, plente of teris ; and after, &thorn;e wyne of swete teris; than
sendys he &thorn;e oyle of consolacio&ntail;, &thorn;at gyffes
&thorn;a&mtail; Sauour, & lyghtnes his knaweliggynge, and schewes to
&thorn;am of his heuenly priuatyse, &thorn;at es hide fro
&thorn;a&mtail; &thorn;at folowes fleschely desyris, and gyffes
&thorn;a&mtail; selfe a&llbar;e to &thorn;e wysedome of &thorn;e
worlde and his fantesyse, and so enflawmes &thorn;am with &thorn;e
blysse of his lufe &thorn;at &thorn;ay taste somedelle, & fele how
swete he es, how gud he es, how luffande he es-bot noghte a&llbar;e
fully.  I wote wele &thorn;at none may fele it fully, bot if his herte
sulde bryste for lykynge of Ioye.  Sayne Austyne telles of a preste
&thorn;at, whe&ntail; he herde any thynge of God &thorn;at lykynge
ware I&ntail;, he weld be so raueschede in Ioye &thorn;at be walde
fa&llbar; downe, and lygge als he ware dede.  And also in &thorn;at
tyme, if mea layde byrnande fyre to his flesche nakide, he felid <MILESTONE
N="275" UNIT="leaf"> it
no more &thorn;an dose a dede corse.  Sayne Bernarde spekes of
&thorn;e wordis of Iob, &thorn;er he sayse Abscondit lucem in manibus,
&thorn;at es at say, `God hase lyghte hyde in his handis.'  &thorn;ou
wote wele, he &thorn;at hase a candi&llbar; lyghte by-twene his
handis, he may hyde it & schewe it at his owen&ntail; wi&llbar;.  So
dose oure Lorde to his chose&ntail; Whe&ntail; he wi&llbar;, he opynis
his handes, and lyghtenes &thorn;am with


 
<!-- 0031.p60-61.txt -->
<PB N="60">


heuenly gladnes; and whe&ntail; he wi&llbar;, be closis his handis,
and withdrawes &thorn;e lykynge & &thorn;e comforthe fro
&thorn;a&mtail;.  He wi&llbar;c noghte &thorn;at &thorn;ay fele it
fully aye, Bot here be gyffes &thorn;a&mtail; as for to taste & sauour
somedele how swete he es, how gud he es: als Dauid sayse, Gustate &amp;
videte quam suauis est Dominus, als ;f God sayd to vs, `be &thorn;;s
comforthe and this lykynge &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;is schorte
ty&mtail; hase of me, &thorn;ou may taste & fele how swete, how gude I
ame to my cbosy&ntail; ;n my blysse, ;n &thorn;e werlde with-
owtte&ntail; ende'; and &thorn;us he dose, for to drawe vs fro worldly
besynes, and &thorn;e lykynge &thorn;er-of, and for to enflawme oure
hertes with lufe-&yogh;ernynges, For to wy&ntail; and to hafe &thorn;e
lykynge of &thorn;at Ioye, a&llbar;e at &thorn;e fu&llbar; in body and
saule, with hym for to be euer more with-owtte&ntail; ende.</P>

<P>A dameselle wyse & wele taghte, &thorn;at me&ntail; calles Gelosye,
&thorn;at es ay wakyre and besy euerylyke wele for to do, sa&llbar;
kepe &thorn;e orloge, and sa&llbar; wakky&ntail; &thorn;e o&thorn;er
ladyse, & make &thorn;a&mtail; arely to ryse, and go &thorn;e
wyllylyere to &thorn;aire seruysse.  &THORN;er es orloges in towne
&thorn;at wakyns me&ntail; to ryse to bodily trauayle, & &thorn;at es
&thorn;e seke; and &thorn;er es orloges in &thorn;e cete &thorn;at
wakynnes &thorn;e marchauntes to wende a-bowte &thorn;aire
marchandyce, &thorn;at es &thorn;e wynde &thorn;at blawes daye.  And
&thorn;er es orloges in religio&ntail; of contemplacio&ntail;.  And
this es of this holy relegyo&ntail; &thorn;at es fundede of&thorn;e
Haly Gaste, and &thorn;is es Ielosy; and t&hbar;is es sauoyre of
perfeccio&ntail;.  & ofte it falles in relegio&ntail;, be-fore
&thorn;at &thorn;e Orloge falles or any belles rynges, Goddes gostely
seruandes are lange wakenede before, and hase wepede by-fore God, and
hase wasche&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail; with &thorn;aire teris, and
&thorn;aire spyrit hase <MILESTONE N="275 bk." UNIT="leaf"> vesete with deuote prayers and gastely
comforthe.  And why rose &thorn;ay so arely & so tymly ? Witterly for
&thorn;e orloge of lufe; and damesele Ielosye had wakened
&thorn;a&mtail; be-fore &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e handmayde
orloge fe&llbar;e.  A, dere bre&thorn;ir and syster! sely ar tho
sawles &thorn;at &thorn;e lufe of God, and longyng ti&llbar; hym,
wakyns, and slomers noghte, no slepis noghte, in &thorn;e slowthe of
fleschly lustes.  For-thi be sayse in Canticis, Ecce dormio, et cor
meum <CORR SIC="vigelat" RESP="Perry">vigilat</CORR>, &thorn;at es at saye, `when I slepe bodily, my flesche
for
<PB N="61">


to cse & ryste, my herte es ay wakyre in gelosy and in lufe-
&yogh;ernynge to Gode.'  That saule &thorn;at &thorn;us wakes to God,
me thynke hole conscyence &thorn;at werldly me&ntail; thynke, and
&thorn;at es this, Jeo ay le quer a leche, rauayle' par amours,
&thorn;at es at saye, `My&ntail; herte es styrte fro me, wakened with
lufe.'  Wbate es this &thorn;at mase &thorn;e herte fro &thorn;e
flesche to wake, and for &thorn;at es it, as it were, fremde to hym?
Wittirly Ieloussye with lufe, teres, & murnynge, with lufe-longynge
consayuede in deuote vprysynge of herte.</P>

<P>When this Abbaye was alle wele ordaynede, and Goddes wi&llbar;
seruede in ryste, & in lykynge, & in pese of saule, than come a
tyrante of &thorn;e lande thorowe his powere, and did in this holy
Abbaye Foure doghtyrs &thorn;at he hade &thorn;at were lothely & of
euy&llbar; maners, &thorn;at &thorn;e fende was fadyr of thiese
doghtyrs.  &THORN;e firste &thorn;er-of, &thorn;is foule barne-tyme,
highte Envye; the to&thorn;er highte Pride; the thirde highte
Gruchynge; the ferthe highte False Demynge of o&thorn;er.  Thiese
foure doghetirs &thorn;an base &thorn;e tyraunt, &thorn;e deue&llbar;
of helle, for euy&llbar; wi&llbar; & malese, done in this holy Abbaye;
and &thorn;ay, with &thorn;aire foule vnclennes, &thorn;e couent hase
greuede and harmede, so &thorn;at &thorn;ay no riste ne no pete may
hafe, nyghte nor daye, nor lykynge in saule. And when &thorn;e gud
lady Charite saw this (&thorn;at was Abbas), and the lady Wysedome
(&thorn;at was prioresse), and &thorn;e lady Mekenes, supprioresse,
and &thorn;e to&thorn;er gude ladyse of this holy Abbaye, that the
holy Abbaye was in poynte for to worthe to noghte thorowe &thorn;e
wykkydnes <MILESTONE N="276" UNIT="leaf">of thir foure, Than range [&thorn;ay] &thorn;e chapetour
belle, and gedirde &thorn;am alle to-gedir, and asked concele whate
was beste to do.  A11d than lady Dyscrecyo&ntail; &thorn;a&mtail;
concelde &thorn;at &thorn;ay solde alle falle in prayere to &thorn;e
Holy Goste, &thorn;at of this Abbay es vesetour, &thorn;at he haste
hym for to come, as &thorn;ay grete myster hade, &thorn;are for to
helpe and vesete with his grace.  And &thorn;ay a&llbar;, at hire
consaile, with grete deuocyo&ntail; of herte vnto hym, sange alle with
a swete steue&ntail;, Veni, creator sriritus!  And also sone &thorn;e
Holy Goste come at &thorn;aire desyrynge, and &thorn;am com- forthede
with his grace, and chasede owte &thorn;e fowle wyghtes, &thorn;ose
lothely fendis doghetirs, and clenesede &thorn;e Abbaye of all

 
